  ],
  "activity_sections": [
    {
      "key": "929f2429-f36c-44fb-8431-cad37d44ba81",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Pre-Assessment"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "929f2429-f36c-44fb-8431-cad37d44ba81",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c8bbe630-8250-48e2-9e00-7e1ed4dc6060"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "487b2372-0c32-441c-80c3-732c92c1c509",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You’re planning a class pizza party that has music and activities! Take a look at this picture—there’s pizza, soda, napkins… all kinds of things to think about. Go to Level 1 and answer the question: What data would you want to collect to plan a party like this?",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "487b2372-0c32-441c-80c3-732c92c1c509",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fc6cdf72-3385-4776-af11-a6b8cb42e88a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "50f3fc21-cca7-4b39-8209-9aca31fb0a19",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 1, Level 1 to record the information (data) they would want to collect to help plan a pizza party.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** This activity introduces students to the idea that data is any information that can help solve a problem or answer a question. In this case, students are imagining they are planning a class pizza party and identifying what information (data) they might need to collect to make the event fun and successful.\n",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Looking at what data the students would want to collect here can help you understand what previous understanding they have of data and the role of data in solving real-world problems.\n"
          },
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This is an intentional pre-assessment — students haven’t formally learned what data is yet, so their responses will give insight into how they naturally think about information and decision-making. Remind students that there are no wrong answers. If they’re stuck, you can prompt them with questions like: “What would you want to know before the party?” or “What kind of things would you need to plan for food, drinks, or activities?” Encourage a range of responses: number of people attending, pizza preferences, drink options, dietary needs, supplies, or even music or activity ideas\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "50f3fc21-cca7-4b39-8209-9aca31fb0a19",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fc6cdf72-3385-4776-af11-a6b8cb42e88a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b39d6c71-51bb-42c7-a0e4-50e7664fbea2",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b39d6c71-51bb-42c7-a0e4-50e7664fbea2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fc6cdf72-3385-4776-af11-a6b8cb42e88a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "023d8fc6-bcce-4460-a71e-e72e413d7262",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Group students into pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have pairs engage in the Compare and Connect protocol by sharing the types of information they listed. Encourage them to compare what was the same or different and discuss why they chose those data points.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students may focus on obvious details (like pizza types or number of people). Push their thinking by prompting them to consider why they chose certain information—what decision would it help them make when planning the party?\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "023d8fc6-bcce-4460-a71e-e72e413d7262",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fc6cdf72-3385-4776-af11-a6b8cb42e88a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d6fea1c4-6dd7-433c-8235-1ac12220047e",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What information did you and your partner want to collect for the party?*\n\n* Call on a few students to share what they found in their Compare and Connect.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This is a quick share-out to help surface patterns in student thinking. Snapping encourages students to actively listen and participate while showing how common certain ideas are. Highlight both common responses (like pizza types or number of guests) and unique ones (like music preferences or cleanup plans) to show how diverse data needs can be.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Insights from Data and AI Unit Guide."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d6fea1c4-6dd7-433c-8235-1ac12220047e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fc6cdf72-3385-4776-af11-a6b8cb42e88a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "987dcc1f-fb15-4830-ad43-62465221c72a",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "All that information you came up with to plan the party—like how many people are coming, what kind of pizza to order, or what music people like—that’s called data. Data is just organized information we can use to help us make decisions.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "987dcc1f-fb15-4830-ad43-62465221c72a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fc6cdf72-3385-4776-af11-a6b8cb42e88a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3ebcf75a-0435-47ed-bc5d-d6d2bace6279",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***data*** and have students record the definition in their Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***data science*** and have students record the definition in their Unit Guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Word Wall, and have students add ***data*** and ***data science*** to the wall.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3ebcf75a-0435-47ed-bc5d-d6d2bace6279",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fc6cdf72-3385-4776-af11-a6b8cb42e88a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b2f00672-cd16-4656-9965-cf386cc2b518",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b2f00672-cd16-4656-9965-cf386cc2b518",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fc6cdf72-3385-4776-af11-a6b8cb42e88a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "52336552-cf0c-4d0d-9067-ce8f007575d3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a Data Scientist tent and a Data Scientist Bingo activity guide. You may have students choose a data scientist, you may choose for them, or you may pass them out randomly.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Each of the data scientists available have articles of different lengths and/or videos them that students can explore to learn more about the person. You may wish to assign students to data scientists based on their reading levels. Each data scientist also comes from a different field, so you may wish to allow students to pick based on their interests – you can have them pick based on job title on the placards or choose a bingo card slot they are interested in researching more about and give them the person who goes with that bingo card slot. If you are pressed for time, random is fine.\n\nThere are 24 available data scientists. Each one has at least one square meant to refer to them on the bingo card. If you do not have 24 students in your class, not every data scientist will be studied by your class. That is ok! Even if your class has the requisite number of students, it is improbable that every student will be introduced to every data scientist."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "52336552-cf0c-4d0d-9067-ce8f007575d3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "727f2853-5d14-488c-9e76-3fe78db69ec1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "78001357-7703-4ec6-9c6e-6e47903adeaa",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "78001357-7703-4ec6-9c6e-6e47903adeaa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "727f2853-5d14-488c-9e76-3fe78db69ec1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c75437ef-1f0c-44da-9241-e2c08eee5325",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "There are data scientists who do organize data for their full time job, but basically everybody uses it somewhere. Today, we’ll explore how several data scientists affect the fields they work in. Each of you will be given one data scientist to represent. After you’ve studied this data scientist, you will represent them while meeting with another person who is representing a different data scientist. As you share information with each other, you’ll fill out your bingo card.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c75437ef-1f0c-44da-9241-e2c08eee5325",
        "lesson_activity.key": "727f2853-5d14-488c-9e76-3fe78db69ec1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "264716be-46ef-460d-b1f7-7f5281c17899",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Students should close their laptops – all information they need should now be on their tents.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students on each side fold their paper with the face and name in front, and their answers to the questions in back. Set up in pairs facing each other for the first conversation. Make sure each student has a pair; if you have an odd number of students have 3 of them talk.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "There are multiple ways to get students facing each other – you can have an outer and inner circle of chairs, or move desks / chairs so they are facing each other at desks. If your room does not allow for any kind of moving furniture, you can have students carry their tents around with them and meet standing up."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "264716be-46ef-460d-b1f7-7f5281c17899",
        "lesson_activity.key": "727f2853-5d14-488c-9e76-3fe78db69ec1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1749fa4e-ae7c-40f5-b127-904a14165967",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1749fa4e-ae7c-40f5-b127-904a14165967",
        "lesson_activity.key": "727f2853-5d14-488c-9e76-3fe78db69ec1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "426ff5de-5790-4794-93c1-029c06beb091",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 2. Once students are on the level, they should find the person they are researching, click on the available link, and answer the questions on their tent about that person as they read about them, in preparation to represent the individual. Give students the time that they need – up to around 10 minutes.",
        "progression_name": "Data Scientists",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Some students may be excited at the prospect of roleplaying a data scientist, but others might be terrified of acting. \"Represent\" the data scientist can mean either – students may either pretend to be the data scientist as they talk, or just tell their fellow student about the data scientist.\n\nIf students complete earlier than other students, encourage them to dive deeper into the person. They may use a search engine to look up the person’s name, or the company they work for and collect more information."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "426ff5de-5790-4794-93c1-029c06beb091",
        "lesson_activity.key": "727f2853-5d14-488c-9e76-3fe78db69ec1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "646ad651-0a2d-4560-bcdd-5c09a3eeb9ae",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "646ad651-0a2d-4560-bcdd-5c09a3eeb9ae",
        "lesson_activity.key": "727f2853-5d14-488c-9e76-3fe78db69ec1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2c6ae5a1-7732-46ea-a06a-750d10a2f4a2",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students face each other for the first conversation. Make sure each student has a pair. If you have an odd number of students, have three of them talk.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students represent their data scientist. They will have conversation with a student. In the meantime, the student who is not actively representing the data scientist they studied should be keeping track of one cool thing they learn on the back of their bingo card, and finding where the data scientist being represented fits on their bingo card. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are on-task. As it gets to approximately the halfway point for time, make sure students are getting to their third data scientist or so (you can tell by how many people they have filled out on their bingo card), and if they haven’t gotten to 3 yet, encourage conversations to be shorter.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Depending on how you like to manage your class, you may want to have regimented timing for each conversation and when they swap, or you may allow students to allow conversations to go on for as long or as short as they’d like, with an eye for making sure students talk about at least 4-5 other data scientists."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2c6ae5a1-7732-46ea-a06a-750d10a2f4a2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "727f2853-5d14-488c-9e76-3fe78db69ec1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f3610020-3a5b-49f1-acbb-d72b9be47277",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Let’s pause to think about ethics. Every data scientist works with people’s information in some way—and that brings up important questions about privacy, fairness, and impact. Talk with your last partner about the ethical concerns your data scientist might face. What kind of data are they working with? Could it be misused? Who benefits from their work—and who might be left out or hurt by it?\n",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f3610020-3a5b-49f1-acbb-d72b9be47277",
        "lesson_activity.key": "727f2853-5d14-488c-9e76-3fe78db69ec1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "71071605-f49d-42dc-bf60-301828bcc3f1",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students discuss the potential ethical concerns related to each of their data scientists with their last partner. If time allows, invite a few students to share one ethical concern they discussed.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are considering the context of their specific data scientist’s work when identifying ethical concerns. Look and listen for responses related to data access, privacy, or potential impact.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students struggle to name an ethical concern, encourage them to think about what would happen if the data was misused or if the data was about them personally.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "71071605-f49d-42dc-bf60-301828bcc3f1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "727f2853-5d14-488c-9e76-3fe78db69ec1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9eeda234-451e-4e8b-bb6d-edee4cf2928a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9eeda234-451e-4e8b-bb6d-edee4cf2928a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3a7ec95f-b526-433e-acc9-90cf89b4d2be"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9784ecc2-789f-4123-a6ed-05d46016cae4",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce data tables.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Where have you seen or used data tables? Where were you? Where did the words or numbers in the data table come from? How did you use it?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** The point of this discussion is just to get a few examples shared out loud that demonstrate the diversity of situations where data tables are found.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***spreadsheet***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have a student add ***spreadsheet*** to the Word Wall.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9784ecc2-789f-4123-a6ed-05d46016cae4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0204e869-b9da-44c8-aebd-24090472fdcc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "72d051ef-f05e-4355-bd91-16b779a70750",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Today, you're going to become data scientists. One of the things that data scientists do is take the time to understand the data they are working with. First, we need some data! You all are going to help generate some data about a class pizza party.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "72d051ef-f05e-4355-bd91-16b779a70750",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0165b81f-e12b-4f98-804e-3737f4e0c49b",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the survey questions.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student two sticky notes.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students write their answers to the questions on separate sticky notes. Invite some (5-10) students to come up, one at a time, and add their sticky notes to a pre-drawn anchor chart.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***data***, and add it to the Spreadsheet Anchor Chart.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***cells***, and add it to the Spreadsheet Anchor Chart.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to define ***rows*** and ***columns***, and add these to the Spreadsheet Anchor Chart.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***attribute***, and add it to the Spreadsheet Anchor Chart.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***case***, and add it to the Spreadsheet Anchor Chart.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***sample size***, and add it to the Spreadsheet Anchor Chart. Note that even though there are 517 rows in this spreadsheet, the sample size is 516 because row number 1 is not data but attribute labels.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***spreadsheet***, and add it to the Spreadsheet Anchor Chart.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Group students into pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 1 to prepare to participate in a Three Reads of Data with their partner on the Pizza Slice dataset.",
        "progression_name": "Read 1: Context",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "While the activity is completed online in a lesson level, it is very important that you use the subsequent slides to lead each reading. Displaying each \"read\" slide helps ensure students progress at the right pace, preventing them from spending excessive time on any single data read. Additionally, these slides serve as useful prompts, reminding students of the specific questions they should consider about the data during each reading."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0165b81f-e12b-4f98-804e-3737f4e0c49b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3bfa3183-8e36-4de1-80f5-6b74d685b112",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3bfa3183-8e36-4de1-80f5-6b74d685b112",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a5304f0e-c139-4462-8553-5080a0753236",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Facilitate a Three Reads of Data about this data set. During Read 1, give students a moment of individual time to think and record their own ideas in the level and a few minutes to share their ideas with their partner.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Take a few minutes to facilitate a whole-class share out. During the whole-class share out, it is recommended that student responses from Level 1 are displayed for everyone to see.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to move on to Level 2 to work on Read 2: Quantities. ",
        "progression_name": "Read 2: Quantities"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a5304f0e-c139-4462-8553-5080a0753236",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "22743e5b-3434-41e3-8433-30b33deb0aec",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***range***, and add it to the Spreadsheet Anchor Chart.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***average***. Explain how spreadsheets assist with calculating averages even when it might be hard to do this manually.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Facilitate the Read 2 for data set. Just like Read 1, during Read 2, give students a moment of individual time to think and record their own ideas and a few minutes to share their ideas with their partner.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Take a few minutes to facilitate a whole-class share out. During the whole-class share out, it is recommended that student responses from Level 2 are displayed for everyone to see.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to move on to Level 3 to work on Read 3: Questions. ",
        "progression_name": "Read 3: Questions"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "22743e5b-3434-41e3-8433-30b33deb0aec",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b785afa3-96a8-425b-a903-498c767bbbb7",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Facilitate the Read 3 for the data set. Just like Read 1 and 2, during Read 3, give students a moment of individual time to think and record their own ideas in the level. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to not just share what questions they came up with during Read 3, but to peer review the questions their partner recorded and give feedback on whether the questions are Relevant, Specific, Actionable, Investigative, and Respectful. Give students time to discuss their feedback with their partner and make adjustments where needed.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "It is important that students have a chance to make adjustments to their Read 3 questions. This will help students understand that it is likely that they will not come up with the perfect question to ask about a dataset the first time, and that iteration on their question to make it an effective one that meets all the criteria is normal and necessary."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b785afa3-96a8-425b-a903-498c767bbbb7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ae92378f-058b-4337-8412-50f5bd86d014",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ae92378f-058b-4337-8412-50f5bd86d014",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f9bcd644-3d84-4200-823f-a0472b6d5d9c",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Take a few minutes to facilitate a whole-class share out. During the whole-class share out, it is recommended that student responses from Level 3 are displayed for everyone to see.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Students’ Three Reads can be used as a formative assessment of their understanding and ability to create effective questions based on the criteria."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f9bcd644-3d84-4200-823f-a0472b6d5d9c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "93e65e3c-ad24-4953-a239-8950597938f4",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain what AI data analytics tools can do to help make sense of large datasets. Then, walk through the YouTube example to show how AI identifies patterns and makes predictions."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "93e65e3c-ad24-4953-a239-8950597938f4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "aa9a83e6-a19b-4f1b-9e35-500dc4b02884",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You’ve started thinking like a data scientist. Now let’s bring in AI as a thinking partner and compare what it notices about the dataset.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "aa9a83e6-a19b-4f1b-9e35-500dc4b02884",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "32ff052e-42b2-46fc-a8bd-85c41bf35de8",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to move on to Level 4 to analyze the data using AI Chat. ",
        "progression_name": "Analyze Data with AI"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "32ff052e-42b2-46fc-a8bd-85c41bf35de8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4cd6062a-536b-46af-90d2-b744e412b688",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair of students a copy of the Answering a Data Question activity guide.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": " Students may notice that this activity guide uses parts of the UMPIRE strategy they’ve learned in a previous unit. If helpful, briefly remind them that they're using steps like **Understand** (interpreting the data), **Produce** (making a recommendation), and **Explain** (justifying their reasoning). You don’t need to reteach the whole strategy—just connect it as a familiar thinking routine to structure their approach.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4cd6062a-536b-46af-90d2-b744e412b688",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e42ff93a-a01a-4377-88de-446db0e26aac",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Tell students that now that they’re done with the Three Reads, they’re ready to explore the full data set. Tell students that their job is to see if they can answer the data question: How much pizza should we order for a school party? Let students know that the full data set includes survey responses from hundreds of students. Prepare students by telling them that while more data can be necessary to answer a question, it can also be more challenging to work with, which is why data scientists use computers to work with large sets of data.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 5 to access the Pizza Slice data set.",
        "progression_name": "Pizza Slice Data Set",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "As students work on this activity guide, circulate and ask a sampling of students the questions from the Activity Guide to assess their understanding of how to read information in a Spreadsheet."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e42ff93a-a01a-4377-88de-446db0e26aac",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bb45ec0e-88bb-4db9-9879-867884600f62",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bb45ec0e-88bb-4db9-9879-867884600f62",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "69b49c4f-64ac-4a69-aca6-345d70887a53",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "69b49c4f-64ac-4a69-aca6-345d70887a53",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "29574e9c-98cf-40b8-8132-eb096e213e48",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "29574e9c-98cf-40b8-8132-eb096e213e48",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bcd68ce5-adcd-4d1c-a4ad-9944ac45c54a",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How much pizza should we order for a school party?*\n\n* Use a Think, Pair, Share to close out this activity with this question from the activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Use this discussion to see how students interpret the data and make decisions using spreadsheet information. Students may come up with different recommendations depending on how many slices they think students should get, how many students they assume will attend, and how they apply the budget. The goal isn’t to agree on one answer, but to justify their reasoning using the data—just like a data scientist would."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bcd68ce5-adcd-4d1c-a4ad-9944ac45c54a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "620646ea-cf28-41da-94d0-0d21d3f3441b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9aeb66ab-e21c-42ee-ac70-4d858405f9ed",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9aeb66ab-e21c-42ee-ac70-4d858405f9ed",
        "lesson_activity.key": "337c6289-6de1-4e19-b3d1-9f4e1521b3f8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "59e2b8c1-4cf3-4215-99d1-0f6e733ed4b9",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What types of data can we gather that might tell us something about our classroom environment? Why might that data be important?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to look around the classroom and name several objects (desk, books, etc.) or traits and preferences of classmates (long or short hair, favorite colors, etc.) and share. Remind students that data is organized information. To get the conversation started, you might suggest a few examples, such as counting the total number of books on different rows of shelves, the frequency of certain titles, number of people with long, medium, or short hair.  In addition to being able to just name things that we might collect data about – number of books, height of desks, etc. – push students to also answer why such data might be important and how it could be used. For example, the frequency of certain titles might give insight into what grade level is primarily taught in the classroom.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students take out a scrap piece of paper.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students work with their partner to collect and write down their data as quickly as possible (about 3-4 minutes). Encourage students to get up and move around as necessary to collect their data.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Assist students with identifying their data and writing down their findings, as necessary. Look for particularly interesting data that is being collected which might offer interesting insights. Use these to help drive the discussion that happens next.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What did you find most surprising about the data you collected?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students are being asked to compare their assumptions versus their actual findings – which demonstrates one of the values of using data science. Sample responses could include:\n* The average desk height in the classroom is 28” which is below the recommended height of 29” - 30” for a high school classroom\n* Books that are about math tend to be colored blue more than any other color – maybe people associate blue with calculation and logic?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How might the data you collected be used to make improvements or changes in our classroom?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to make the connection between gathering of data and its potential real-world impacts. This can underscore how data is often used to drive decisions. \nSample responses could include:\n* The ratio of short hair vs. longer hair is 3 to 1. This might indicate that summer is coming and it’s getting warmer outside, or it might indicate that the current fashion trends are for shorter styles for both men and women.\n* I feel as though our desks are too short, and I feel as though I am hunching over all of the time. Now, with this data that indicates that the height is below average, I can make an argument to the school board that we should invest in desks that are ergonomically designed for high school students so that they will be able to perform better.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the learning objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "59e2b8c1-4cf3-4215-99d1-0f6e733ed4b9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c20f1e8e-2a3d-4cdc-afdc-66bb2cd61ce8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fa106787-9487-4349-804d-be8198ec37e7",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***data collection***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***data ethics***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Levels 1-3. On each level, they'll read a scenario, choose the person they agree with most, and explain why in the free response box. These scenarios will help them prepare for a whole-class 4 Corners discussion about each scenario on ethical decision-making in data collection.\n* **Level 1:** Students read the scenario and decide which person they agree with regarding collecting data about food allergies. \n* **Level 2:** Students read the scenario and decide which person they agree with regarding collecting data about getting sponsorships.\n* **Level 3:** Students read the scenario and decide which person they agree with regarding collecting data about music choices. ",
        "progression_name": "Party Planning",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students are unsure which person to agree with, encourage them to ask themselves:\n* What type of data is being collected?\n* Could it be risky or make someone uncomfortable?\n* Who benefits — and who might be impacted?\n\nThese questions can help students evaluate each person's approach based on privacy, consent, and fairness—not just personal preference.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fa106787-9487-4349-804d-be8198ec37e7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a42469fa-dc78-41e2-971e-f8bc612c22a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d99f8db6-2d33-4b3a-992f-a07a531f596b",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students write, check responses or prompt with light questions to encourage deeper thinking. Focus on how they’re weighing trade-offs around privacy, consent, fairness, or inclusion.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** After students finish all three levels, facilitate a 4 Corners discussion about each scenario. Ask students to pick the person they most agreed with from each scenario and stand in that corner. If they didn’t agree with anyone fully, they can choose \"Other.\" \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** After each corner shares, ask the class any of the follow-up questions listed below that would help push their thinking about ethical data collection based on what was shared by each corner: \n* What value did that person prioritize (e.g., privacy, consent, fairness)?\n* Could their choice unintentionally harm someone or leave someone out?\n* Was there a better way to collect or protect the data?\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": " Encourage students to build off each other’s reasoning. There’s no single right answer—what matters is how they justify the ethical implications of data collection choices.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d99f8db6-2d33-4b3a-992f-a07a531f596b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a42469fa-dc78-41e2-971e-f8bc612c22a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "57383188-9427-49f8-9736-74312ee4d84b",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 4 and write a statement that provides ethical guidance for collecting data about people. Remind them to think about what they learned from the three scenarios and discussions — especially around issues like privacy, consent, accuracy, and fairness.\n\n\n\n",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "57383188-9427-49f8-9736-74312ee4d84b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a42469fa-dc78-41e2-971e-f8bc612c22a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fa12723a-192b-4a1d-8184-588e6c35b53a",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** After students submit, display a few responses using the “Show Responses” feature. Highlight strong ethical principles or creative ways students expressed the values they discussed."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fa12723a-192b-4a1d-8184-588e6c35b53a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a42469fa-dc78-41e2-971e-f8bc612c22a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "64449fcb-6314-4f57-bc68-ba840da67429",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This visual represents some of the important themes regarding data ethics that arose from the party planning scenarios that you all explored. When you think about how you are collecting and using data, these three categories should be used to help assess the ethics of what you are proposing. An important concept that came up in the final scenario was the idea of bias.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "64449fcb-6314-4f57-bc68-ba840da67429",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a42469fa-dc78-41e2-971e-f8bc612c22a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a01b8942-7b41-42a9-916c-252afe64dc17",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the three components of data ethics.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How might AI tools be used to collect this kind of data?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should identify ways AI can collect data automatically—through apps, sensors, social media, or surveillance—and describe how that might look in real-world contexts.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What ethical concerns come up when AI is involved in data collection?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should raise ethical concerns such as lack of consent, invasion of privacy, potential bias in how AI collects or interprets data, and misuse of sensitive information.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***bias***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair several sticky notes and a pair of scissors.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students group the datasets and discuss how they might group them based on how the data might have been collected. They should use sticky notes to label their classifications.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Challenge students to come up with thorough descriptions of the collection methods that they are grouping together on their sticky notes. Remind them that it is alright to change their minds and to reorganize as new realizations and discoveries come to light. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students might be tempted to try to group the datasets by topic and similarity in theme, rather than in the method that they might have been collected. Remind students of this as they work, if necessary. If it is helpful for your students, show the Possible Data Collection Methods slide to give them a starting point.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a01b8942-7b41-42a9-916c-252afe64dc17",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a42469fa-dc78-41e2-971e-f8bc612c22a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0c20e5d2-71e6-4f09-b2c6-62d99aef6610",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0c20e5d2-71e6-4f09-b2c6-62d99aef6610",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a42469fa-dc78-41e2-971e-f8bc612c22a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b0b0b5c3-97b0-4732-98f8-e8ef02ef9437",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are some ways your group grouped the different collection methods?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Three of the main methods for collecting data that might emerge from the activity include:\n* Website, app, or automated data collection. Usually this data is collected automatically based on a program or script that might be running.\n* Survey data. This involves composing qualitative and quantitative questions that are then distributed to an audience to answer.\n* Measurements (sensors or other measurement devices). This includes data that is collected from instrumentation of some type. The recording of it can be automated or manual.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Share the example methods for collecting data that emerged from the previous activity. Ask students to come up with additional examples of data that could be collected using each of these methods to reinforce their understanding of how each collection method works.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What method of data collection might the AI in YouTube recommendations use, and what ethical concerns are raised?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** There are a variety of different ways in which the AI recommendation engine in YouTube might collect data. Some of it is voluntary– thumbs up or down, subscribing to content creators– and some of it is hidden from the user– watch history, clicks, and time spent on videos. This might raise a variety of different ethical concerns such as a lack of transparency for how the algorithm decides what to offer. It might profile users based on their interactions and the data that is collected without the user being able to see how they are being represented in the system. Also, there exists the possibility that a user might be shown videos with the intent to influence or affect their opinions and behavior without consent."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b0b0b5c3-97b0-4732-98f8-e8ef02ef9437",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a42469fa-dc78-41e2-971e-f8bc612c22a6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3145877e-0425-444a-9a40-ea1ad7c22609",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3145877e-0425-444a-9a40-ea1ad7c22609",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bff339f2-1310-4180-b16d-809b28c78184"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7f087c8b-95f2-4175-b748-ff7beebcf739",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Once you delete your social media account, all your data is required to be immediately removed from the company's servers.*\n\n* Have students read the statement and discuss with a partner. If they think it is true, they should indicate with a thumbs up. If they think it is false, they should indicate with a thumbs down. Then briefly discuss the statement as a class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This statement is false. No federal law requires immediate deletion of data upon account termination. Data can remain on servers for a significant period due to backups and other technical reasons. Immediate deletion is rarely practiced.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "It may be worth noting with students that there are no universally accepted data rights. This activity will focus on the current laws within the United States. There are often discrepancies between states when a federal law has not been adopted that addresses a particular aspect of data rights.\n\nAs an optional follow-up question, you could ask students: *Why might companies retain data even after you delete your account?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7f087c8b-95f2-4175-b748-ff7beebcf739",
        "lesson_activity.key": "547a54da-9451-4fd8-80d2-cd8a317400c4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "381aa957-40e8-4f12-a070-4d9a8b2b4121",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "381aa957-40e8-4f12-a070-4d9a8b2b4121",
        "lesson_activity.key": "547a54da-9451-4fd8-80d2-cd8a317400c4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0bcfcbc7-3297-46a4-9faa-5a8386b4fa13",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *All personal data collected with consent can be kept by the company indefinitely.*\n\n* Have students read the statement and discuss with a partner. If they think it is true, they should indicate with a thumbs up. If they think it is false, they should indicate with a thumbs down. Then briefly discuss the statement as a class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This statement is false. There are privacy laws that say that even with consent, companies should only keep what is necessary and only for a reasonable time limit.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "As an optional follow-up question, you could ask students: *What are the potential risks of indefinite data retention?*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0bcfcbc7-3297-46a4-9faa-5a8386b4fa13",
        "lesson_activity.key": "547a54da-9451-4fd8-80d2-cd8a317400c4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "93fe6aa6-4fff-4396-b54f-ec8405a2fb45",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "93fe6aa6-4fff-4396-b54f-ec8405a2fb45",
        "lesson_activity.key": "547a54da-9451-4fd8-80d2-cd8a317400c4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a78dbf6d-63cd-4cde-a7fe-002720990d16",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Businesses need your consent to share anonymized data about you with other people or companies.*\n\n* Have students read the statement and discuss with a partner. If they think it is true, they should indicate with a thumbs up. If they think it is false, they should indicate with a thumbs down. Then briefly discuss the statement as a class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This statement is false. U.S. laws generally do not require consent for sharing data that has been properly anonymized, as it is no longer considered personal data.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "As an optional follow-up question, you could ask students: *Are there any risks still associated with anonymized data?*\n\nAn interesting extension activity here could be to have students explore [**Data Privacy Lab**](https://dataprivacylab.org/) to see how anonymized data can be less anonymous that one might think. It is a common misconception that an anonymization process is unable to be reverse-engineered."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a78dbf6d-63cd-4cde-a7fe-002720990d16",
        "lesson_activity.key": "547a54da-9451-4fd8-80d2-cd8a317400c4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3a7317c0-be6f-43f3-b96a-e9bbd5767c85",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3a7317c0-be6f-43f3-b96a-e9bbd5767c85",
        "lesson_activity.key": "547a54da-9451-4fd8-80d2-cd8a317400c4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "44e66882-ac4d-4bcc-a086-3bd1e20f0ac1",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "44e66882-ac4d-4bcc-a086-3bd1e20f0ac1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "547a54da-9451-4fd8-80d2-cd8a317400c4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ab4dd8cd-55f1-4b8f-8290-a4fe3a2acb7e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "One of the important ideas that we are going to explore today is the concept of data rights. By the end of class today, I hope that you all will be able to have a better understanding of what data rights you might have as an individual and where you think that those rights can be strengthened or updated.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ab4dd8cd-55f1-4b8f-8290-a4fe3a2acb7e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7b6a0d78-ecc7-493e-9b00-98dc2ce4a4d5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "000dc1a6-3fb4-4fbd-a40f-aacca3620439",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Define ***data rights***.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *When you download a new app or sign up at a new website, do you read the Privacy Policy or simply click Accept and move on?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Student answers will vary. The first activity will have students examining some statements that are seen in the privacy policies of popular applications. This serves as a focusing question for the activity.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How do AI tools like voice assistants or facial recognition systems raise new data rights questions?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Student answers will vary. Students should recognize that AI tools can collect sensitive personal data (like voice or facial features), sometimes continuously, and this raises concerns about consent, storage, and how that data is used or shared.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Should AI systems be required to forget your data if you delete your account?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Student answers will vary. Students should consider that even after deletion, AI systems may retain patterns learned from user data. Students may raise questions about whether true deletion is possible and what ethical responsibility companies have.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student one of the Privacy Policy Statements.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students find a partner. Students should take turns reading the privacy policy statement and discussing the reflection question. After the discussion, students should mark an X on the line to reflect how they feel about the privacy policy statement. Students will then switch cards with one another, find another partner, and repeat the process.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As the students participate in this activity, listen to their discussion and encourage them to dive deeper into topics that might arise. While responses will certainly vary, students might be surprised at how long companies can keep their data, wonder about what kinds of information companies choose to store, question the need to share information with others, and feel as though the policy statements give too much freedom to companies. The pace of the activity should be quick enough so that each discussion should be brief, but impactful. If there are an odd number of students, then you might consider having students form small groups of three.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How did these privacy policy statements affect your perception of your personal data rights?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students responses to this prompt will vary. The following themes might develop from discussion:\n* Students might have increased awareness of how much data that they are giving away\n* They might express concerns about the possible misuse of their personal data\n* Students might feel as though there is little that they can do to affect the ways that their data is being collected and used\n* There can be an increased urge to understand how data is collected and to protect their privacy in a more active way"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "000dc1a6-3fb4-4fbd-a40f-aacca3620439",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7b6a0d78-ecc7-493e-9b00-98dc2ce4a4d5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "313f82c5-e969-4fb5-80ae-08f8f95b42a2",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In our next activity, we are going to examine different stakeholders in the data rights debate, each of whom have different experiences and attitudes towards data rights. You will be asked to examine and discuss the stance of your stakeholder towards  the topic of data rights.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "313f82c5-e969-4fb5-80ae-08f8f95b42a2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7b6a0d78-ecc7-493e-9b00-98dc2ce4a4d5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5e3bc9c3-1373-42dd-ad50-7bfc0dd9063d",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs or small groups of three.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 1. Students will choose a stakeholder (or you may assign each pair one of the personas) and discuss what their stance towards data rights might be based on their background and key experiences. Students will then write 1-2 data rights statements that would reflect the viewpoint of this stakeholder based on his/her key experiences.",
        "progression_name": "Choose a Stakeholder"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5e3bc9c3-1373-42dd-ad50-7bfc0dd9063d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7b6a0d78-ecc7-493e-9b00-98dc2ce4a4d5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "691fb045-aa2c-40d8-b311-036ae3289a29",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students begin to draft their data rights statements for the various stakeholders, encourage them to explain how the background or key experiences helped to shape the statements that they are drafting.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Data Rights Exploration activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students jigsaw into mixed groups that represent all six of the different stakeholders. They will share key information about their personas and discuss whether or not they agree with the data rights statements. After all members of the group share, have students record in their activity guide the main points and concerns that they have discussed.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Listen to the conversations that are occurring in the classroom and choose several interesting or thoughtful responses to highlight for the class."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "691fb045-aa2c-40d8-b311-036ae3289a29",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7b6a0d78-ecc7-493e-9b00-98dc2ce4a4d5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "009dccf1-b828-4eb8-8d6d-726eff454be4",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "009dccf1-b828-4eb8-8d6d-726eff454be4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3ba181f8-e1e9-4700-b18d-e82f0bc1838b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c99252b4-1afe-4300-8d1b-d7bcb625877a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Group students into pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 1 to prepare to participate in a Three Reads of Data with their partner on the School Party dataset.",
        "progression_name": "Read 1: Context",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "To make the Three Reads more interactive and collaborative, consider printing out the School Party dataset and having students do Read 1 and Read 2 in small groups using sticky notes instead of online. Each group can:\n* Annotate the dataset directly (e.g., highlight patterns or unfamiliar terms).\n* Use sticky notes to write their answers to prompts like “This data is from…” or “The sample size is...”\n* Share out one insight from each group before moving on to Read 3 online.\n\nThis option may increase student engagement and reduce screen fatigue at the start of the lesson.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c99252b4-1afe-4300-8d1b-d7bcb625877a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7070e815-0337-4757-a573-1dde13a298cc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b021b493-d74a-41d5-a94d-ecb763dff5d2",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Present the following scenario: Their school’s leadership class/principal is wants to have an end of the year party and decided to survey students. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Facilitate a Three Reads of Data about this data set. During Read 1, give students a moment of individual time to think and record their own ideas in the level and a few minutes to share their ideas with their partner.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "While the activity is completed online in a lesson level, it is very important that you use the subsequent slides to lead each reading. Displaying each \"read\" slide helps ensure students progress at the right pace, preventing them from spending excessive time on any single data read. Additionally, these slides serve as useful prompts, reminding students of the specific questions they should consider about the data during each reading."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b021b493-d74a-41d5-a94d-ecb763dff5d2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7070e815-0337-4757-a573-1dde13a298cc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b10ded28-a60e-4a03-9aac-1c24b68b0b21",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Take a few minutes to facilitate a whole-class share out. During the whole-class share out, it is recommended that student responses from Level 1 are displayed for everyone to see.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to move on to Level 2 to work on Read 2: Quantities. ",
        "progression_name": "Read 2: Quantities"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b10ded28-a60e-4a03-9aac-1c24b68b0b21",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7070e815-0337-4757-a573-1dde13a298cc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "50f593f8-d618-4a39-afad-1eebfcc7ef00",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Facilitate the Read 2 for data set. Just like Read 1, during Read 2, give students a moment of individual time to think and record their own ideas and a few minutes to share their ideas with their partner.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Inform students that before they complete Read 3, we are going to take a look at some questions and they will need to determine if the questions would be good, okay, or bad questions to ask about the School Party dataset. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Take a few minutes to facilitate a whole-class share out. During the whole-class share out, it is recommended that student responses from Level 2 are displayed for everyone to see.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Inform students that before they complete Read 3, we are going to take a look at some questions and they will need to determine if the questions would be good, okay, or bad questions to ask about the School Party dataset. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Possible Questions activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to skip \"Read 3\" for now and take a look at the Possible Questions activity guide. Have students work with their partner to categorize each question, making sure to discuss their reasons with their partner. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students are categorizing the questions, listen to their discussions, noting any misconceptions or insightful reasoning to highlight in the later class discussion. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "50f593f8-d618-4a39-afad-1eebfcc7ef00",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7070e815-0337-4757-a573-1dde13a298cc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "774a74bf-e5d1-43d7-8f94-93aedc44fb11",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are some characteristics you and your partner noticed that might make a question a good question to ask about a dataset?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should share their characteristic ideas. As they share, ask follow up questions or ask students to use one of the sentences as an example. Try to lead students towards the following criteria:\n* Relevant \n* Specific\n* Actionable\n* Investigative\n* Respectful\n\nAs students come up with characteristics that match, or closely match this criteria, write them down on the board or on a poster for everyone to see.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Do AI systems always ask ethical questions?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Student answers will vary. Students might say that AI can ask questions that feel off, unfair, or too personal because it doesn’t understand context or emotions.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What’s missing when AI writes questions from data without context?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Student answers will vary. Students might say AI doesn’t know the purpose of the data, what’s sensitive, or what’s actually important to ask. This builds the case for human involvement in crafting clear, relevant, and respectful questions.\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Criteria for Creating Effective Questions guided notes.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the \"Relevant\" criteria and have students complete the guided notes. Make reference back to anything the students pointed out during the share out of what made a question a \"good\" question. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which of these questions would be \"Good\", \"Okay\", or \"Bad\" based on being relevant for a dataset containing information about students’ sports activities and students’ grades?*\n\n* Use Think-Pair-Share to allow students to individually reflect, discuss with a partner, and then share their thoughts as a class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** \n1. This is a bad question. It is not relevant since it is not covered by the dataset. Follow up question: *Can this question be tweaked to be relevant?* Since the dataset does not include sports brand preferences, there is not way to tweak this question.\n2. This is a good question. It is relevant to the data provided because it includes attributes that are found in the dataset.\n3. This is a bad or possible okay question. It is not relevant due to “study time” not being covered by the dataset Follow up question: *Can this question be tweaked to be relevant?* This question can be tweaked by modifying it to “Which sports are associated with the highest and lowest grades?” This modified question uses existing data to infer about the academic demands of different sports without needing specific study time data.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students fill in the blanks in the “Examples: Good, Bad, or Okay Questions” column to indicate which Relevant examples are “good”, “bad”, or “okay”.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students should only be considering the \"Relevant\" criteria when classifying these questions. \n* A good question would be one that is relevant to the dataset. \n* An okay question is one that has some parts that are relevant to the dataset and some that are not. \n* A bad question is one that is completely unrelated and not relevant to the dataset. \n\nHowever, some okay and bad questions could potentially be modified to be more relevant. When going over the three \"relevant\" questions, encourage students to try to tweak the okay and bad questions to make them more relevant. This will help highlight the idea that you will probably need to iterate on your data questions before they are effective ones to be asking of data."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "774a74bf-e5d1-43d7-8f94-93aedc44fb11",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f411c0e2-8421-4aae-af0e-1bccbebde331",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f411c0e2-8421-4aae-af0e-1bccbebde331",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "66d5d0fa-6f9a-41a1-a91e-94041ba3212a",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the \"Specific\" criteria and have students complete the guided notes. Make reference back to anything the students pointed out during the share out of what made a question a \"good\" question. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which of these questions would be \"Good\", \"Okay\", or \"Bad\" based on being relevant for a dataset containing daily records of students' self-reported moods and activities at school?*\n\n* Use Think-Pair-Share to allow students to individually reflect, discuss with a partner, and then share their thoughts as a class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** \n1. This is an okay question. The term \"enjoy\" is broad and could encompass many different aspects of the school day. Follow up question: *Can this question be tweaked to be specific?* Modify the question to: “What percentage of students report a positive mood during major school activities such as classes, lunch and recess?” This question narrows down “enjoyment” to specific times and types of activities, making is more specific.\n2. This is an okay question. The question is unclear because it does not specify which activities or how the effect on mood is measured. Follow up question: *Can this question be tweaked to be specific?* Modify the question to: “How do specific school activities (like assemblies or sports) correlate with changes in students' mood ratings on the same day?” This question clarifies which aspects of school activities are being considered and connects them directly to mood changes.\n3. This is a good question. It pinpoints exactly what you want to find out and is specific about days of the week and “happy” as the specific mood. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students fill in the blanks in the “Examples: Good, Bad, or Okay Questions” column to indicate which Specific examples are “good”, “bad”, or “okay”.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students should only be considering the “Specific” criteria when classifying these questions. \n* A good question would be one that is specific without any subjective or broad language. \n* An okay question is one that has some parts that are specific and some that are not. \n* A bad question is one that is completely subjective and broad. \n\nHowever, some okay and bad questions could potentially be modified to be more specific. When going over the three “specific” questions, encourage students to try to tweak the okay and bad questions to make them more specific. This will help highlight the idea that you will probably need to iterate on your data questions before they are effective ones to be asking of data."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "66d5d0fa-6f9a-41a1-a91e-94041ba3212a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c8d7d442-1a6b-47c1-8478-ac106811d40c",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c8d7d442-1a6b-47c1-8478-ac106811d40c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2f2091d3-a74a-4d22-873a-c52014848a88",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the \"Actionable\" criteria and have students complete the guided notes. Make reference back to anything the students pointed out during the share out of what made a question a \"good\" question. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which of these questions would be \"Good\", \"Okay\", or \"Bad\" based on being relevant for a dataset containing survey results from students about their cafeteria food preferences?*\n\n* Use Think-Pair-Share to allow students to individually reflect, discuss with a partner, and then share their thoughts as a class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This question is useful for deciding whether to introduce more diverse cuisines that reflect the cultural backgrounds of the student body\n1. This is a good question. This is an okay question. The question is too vague; \"like\" is not specific enough for actionable feedback. Follow up question: *Can this question be tweaked to be clear and specific?* Modify the question to: “What specific improvements would students recommend for the dishes currently served in the cafeteria?” This revised question solicits specific feedback that can be acted upon rather than a general sentiment.\n2. This is an bad question. \"Enjoy\" is subjective and does not directly lead to a clear action. Follow up question: *Can this question be tweaked to be clear and specific?* Modify the question to: “Would extending the lunch period by 10 minutes lead to a higher rate of meal consumption among students?” This revised question focuses on a specific, measurable outcome (meal consumption) related to a potential actionable change (extending the lunch period).\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students fill in the blanks in the “Examples: Good, Bad, or Okay Questions” column to indicate which Actionable examples are “good”, “bad”, or “okay”.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students should only be considering the “Actionable” criteria when classifying these questions. \n* A good question would be one that leads to actions or decisions that can make things better or provide new insights. \n* An okay question is one that has some parts that are actionable and some that are not. \n* A bad question is one that in no part leads to actions or decisions that can help someone make decisions or provide new insights. \n\nHowever, some okay and bad questions could potentially be modified to be more actionable. When going over the three “actionable” questions, encourage students to try to tweak the okay and bad questions to make them more actionable. This will help highlight the idea that you will probably need to iterate on your data questions before they are effective ones to be asking of data."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2f2091d3-a74a-4d22-873a-c52014848a88",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3b0ab326-cbda-4e29-bd02-42ff66e46b27",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3b0ab326-cbda-4e29-bd02-42ff66e46b27",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c62eb7dd-291c-4cd0-a977-b425d56950ed",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the \"Investigative\" criteria and have students complete the guided notes. Make reference back to anything the students pointed out during the share out of what made a question a \"good\" question. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which of these questions would be \"Good\", \"Okay\", or \"Bad\" based on being relevant for a dataset that shows how much time students spend on homework daily and their average test scores?*\n\n* Use Think-Pair-Share to allow students to individually reflect, discuss with a partner, and then share their thoughts as a class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** \n1. This is a good question. The question contains quantifiable data points - “more than 30 minutes” - and relates it directly to another quantifiable outcome - “average test scores”. This makes it possible to perform analysis to see if there is a correlation or causation between the time spent on homework and test scores.\n2. This is a bad question. The question doesn’t contain any data points that can be analyzed or investigated. Follow up question: *Can this question be tweaked to be investigative?* Modify the question to: “Is there a correlation between the amount of time spent on homework and improvements in test scores?” This question focuses on measurable changes in test scores, which can be analyzed and investigated statistically.\n3. This is an okay question. While it does have one data point that can be investigated, number of days a week, “happiness” is subjective and can not be analyzed. Follow up question: *Can this question be tweaked to be investigative?* Modify the question to: “Does the amount of time spent on homework correlate with students' academic performance, and can this be an indicator of academic stress?” While this question doesn't directly measure happiness, it can indirectly explore whether high volumes of homework might be associated with lower performance, which could be a stress indicator.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students fill in the blanks in the “Examples: Good, Bad, or Okay Questions” column to indicate which Investigative examples are “good”, “bad”, or “okay”.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students should only be considering the “Investigative” criteria when classifying these questions. \n* A good question would be one that lets you use tools, graphs, or calculations to figure out the answer. \n* An okay question is one that has some parts that are investigative and some that are not. \n* A bad question is one that in no part is respectful of people’s feelings and privacy but instead could make someone uncomfortable or expose private information. \n\nHowever, some okay and bad questions could potentially be modified to be more respectful. When going over the three “respectful” questions, encourage students to try to tweak the okay and bad questions to make them able to be respectful. This will help highlight the idea that you will probably need to iterate on your data questions before they are effective ones to be asking of data."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c62eb7dd-291c-4cd0-a977-b425d56950ed",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0a85dc7d-0a9a-42c0-a59a-05e0d311cf4f",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0a85dc7d-0a9a-42c0-a59a-05e0d311cf4f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3caa54b6-0468-40e6-bd29-d98dc9c037aa",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Use the slide to explain what the “Respectful” criteria means. Instruct students to fill out their guided notes with the information on the slide. Make reference back to anything the students pointed out during the share out of what made a question a “good” question. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which of these questions would be \"Good\", \"Okay\", or \"Bad\" based on being relevant for a dataset that contains survey results from students about their music preferences?*\n\n* Use Think-Pair-Share to allow students to individually reflect, discuss with a partner, and then share their thoughts as a class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** \n1. This is a bad question. This question makes a prejudicial assumption that certain music preferences are linked to negative behaviors. It risks stigmatizing students based on their musical tastes and can lead to discrimination or unfair treatment. Follow up question: *Can this question be tweaked to be more ethical and respectful?* Modified question: “How does students' preference in music genres correlate with their participation in school activities?” Rather than attempting to link music preferences to behaviors, refocus the question on understanding the broader influence of music. This question remains within the scope of music preferences and school engagement without making judgments about behavior.\n2. This is a good question. The question is a straightforward, ethical question. It is respectful as it simply seeks to understand general trends in music preferences among students without delving into personal or sensitive areas.\n3. This is a bad question. This question is problematic both ethically and in terms of respectfulness. It attempts to link music preferences—an aspect of personal entertainment and expression—to mental health status, which is a sensitive and private matter. Such an inquiry can lead to stigmatization and misinterpretation, and it's based on an unfounded assumption that one's taste in music can accurately indicate mental health conditions. Follow up question: *Can this question be tweaked to be more ethical and respectful?* Modified question: “Does listening to certain genres of music influence students' reported mood during school hours?” The only way to modify this question is to shift the focus from “mental health” to “reported mood” which can be more safely and ethically explored within the scope of a basic survey about music preferences.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students fill in the blanks in the “Examples: Good, Bad, or Okay Questions” column to indicate which Respectful examples are “good”, “bad”, or “okay”.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students should only be considering the “Respectful” criteria when classifying these questions. \n* A good question would be one that respect people’s privacy and feelings. \n* An okay question is one that has some parts that are respectful and some that are not. \n* A bad question is one that in no part let’s you break down your question using the data to get clear answers with tools, graphs, or calculations. \n\nHowever, some okay and bad questions could potentially be modified to be more investigative. When going over the three “investigative” questions, encourage students to try to tweak the okay and bad questions to make them able to be analyzed or investigated. This will help highlight the idea that you will probably need to iterate on your data questions before they are effective ones to be asking of data."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3caa54b6-0468-40e6-bd29-d98dc9c037aa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b75209de-9888-45d8-8988-8527ba1e1215",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
