    {
      "key": "5891df56-047d-492d-a8bd-50545ceaefec",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How and why would you use the RSAIR criteria?*\n\n* Allow students to reflect on their own and share with a partner if time allows before sharing ideas with the class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Goals for this question include:\n* The criteria should help you think about the kinds of questions a dataset can answer based on what information is there\n* Use the criteria to shape the questions you ask about a dataset so they are clear, directly linked to the data, possible to answer and respectful\n* The criteria will help you end up with a solid data-question that leads to meaningful and responsible insights from your data\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to display potential responses to the question.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students return to the Possible Questions Activity Guide and complete Part 2. They should now be ready to write a new question they think meets all the RSAIR criteria and practice revising the vague question, “What do students like?”, until it’s strong enough to pass the RSAIR test. Remind students they can look back at their notes, previous examples, or class discussion to help.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 3 to participate in Read 3 of the School Party dataset with their partner.",
        "progression_name": "Read 3: Questions",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "While the activity is completed online in a lesson level, it is very important that you use the subsequent slides to lead each reading. Displaying each \"read\" slide helps ensure students progress at the right pace, preventing them from spending excessive time on any single data read. Additionally, these slides serve as useful prompts, reminding students of the specific questions they should consider about the data during each reading."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5891df56-047d-492d-a8bd-50545ceaefec",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "60efe669-8bf8-4536-bb24-ab46bb2b7e0d",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "60efe669-8bf8-4536-bb24-ab46bb2b7e0d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c11746e8-d578-4510-9c30-bff34f9fca8c",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Facilitate the Read 3 for the School Party data set. Just like Read 1 and 2, during Read 3, give students a moment of individual time to think and record their own ideas in the level. Let students know that while coming up with questions that could be asked of the School Party dataset, they can also use the questions on the back from the “Possible Questions” chart. If there were questions that can be made better with some modifications, make sure students make those modifications before adding the question to the Read 3 box.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to not just share what questions they came up with during Read 3, but to peer review the questions their partner recorded and give feedback on whether the questions are Relevant, Specific, Actionable, Investigative, and Respectful. Give students time to discuss their feedback with their partner and make adjustments where needed.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "It is important that students have a chance to make adjustments to their Read 3 questions. This will help students understand that it is likely that they will not come up with the perfect question to ask about a dataset the first time, and that iteration on their question to make it an effective one that meets all the criteria is normal and necessary."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c11746e8-d578-4510-9c30-bff34f9fca8c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1156f4c2-e13b-47fa-b690-b27e7e631609",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1156f4c2-e13b-47fa-b690-b27e7e631609",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6d63dbee-bfd3-4376-9721-59eab7082a01",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Take a few minutes to facilitate a whole-class share out. During the whole-class share out, it is recommended that student responses from Level 3 are displayed for everyone to see.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Highlight questions that meet all RSAIR criteria. For questions that don’t meet all criteria, take a moment and facilitate discussion on how to iterate on the question to make it more effective."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Students’ Three Reads can be used as a formative assessment of their understanding and ability to create effective questions based on the criteria."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6d63dbee-bfd3-4376-9721-59eab7082a01",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "14f21300-7bb8-4125-8a6f-ac4e7fbad48d",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 4 to complete the Check for Understanding.",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This level can be used as a formative assessment of their understanding of and ability to recognize the RSAIR criteria."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "14f21300-7bb8-4125-8a6f-ac4e7fbad48d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0f1a0c94-3442-468f-afe6-d7c5fa239146",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0f1a0c94-3442-468f-afe6-d7c5fa239146",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "affa835b-1f6e-447c-a7d2-ff2b9e2552c8",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Let’s see how AI can help you sharpen your question and push it further using the RSAIR criteria.Think of AI as your revision partner. Ask it for feedback, take what’s useful, and use it to make your question stronger.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "affa835b-1f6e-447c-a7d2-ff2b9e2552c8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "20e1f722-667e-4b83-b05e-5e4a9002786d",
      "position": 19,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to move on to Level 5 and open AI Chat to begin evaluating their question.",
        "progression_name": "Evaluate Data Questions with AI"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "20e1f722-667e-4b83-b05e-5e4a9002786d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "67b461fa-3886-4f2a-a2d5-75fd968ae6fb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d8afdd8f-204e-4ff1-8978-ab1532ac5ed7",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n\n\n",
        "progression_name": "Lacking Criteria",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d8afdd8f-204e-4ff1-8978-ab1532ac5ed7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "31ffcd49-fbb9-4ac2-ae3c-2e4538b893d8"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "81ab45f1-45f8-44d6-b3a2-96b59270158f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students silently think about what story this visualization might be telling.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students might want to simply interpret the visualization by explaining what the data is indicating. Encourage students to go beyond this level of thinking and ask them to think about the people, the countries, the economies, and the culture that might exist behind the visualization. This is an act of inference that will be based upon what kind of background knowledge that the students might have about the visualization that is shown. Therefore, there will be a variety of responses and depths of response."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "81ab45f1-45f8-44d6-b3a2-96b59270158f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f93e4da6-b831-4a05-8fd3-4def3d469016"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0c41708e-7aea-4167-a997-3b53a441b746",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0c41708e-7aea-4167-a997-3b53a441b746",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f93e4da6-b831-4a05-8fd3-4def3d469016"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "24d0e216-2b16-4612-85f2-07fe03080b81",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students turn to a neighbor to discuss their thoughts about the visualization.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What data story does this tell about the people of Africa? What data story might it tell about other regions of the world?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** There are many possible narratives that students might come up with in this activity. Here are some samples:\n* Bank accounts aren’t an option for most Africans. But thanks to mobile money, they don’t need one.\n* Smartphones have changed everything. The unbanked can send and receive cash. They can settle bills. Get their wages. Buy goods and services. Save. Invest.\n* More money moves from mobile phones in sub-Saharan Africa than anywhere in the world. It’s leading the fintech revolution.\n* If the rest of the world wants Africa to buy their products, they should make mobile payments available."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "24d0e216-2b16-4612-85f2-07fe03080b81",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f93e4da6-b831-4a05-8fd3-4def3d469016"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0d905348-7fe9-46b5-a512-06b65d7eaab6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce data storytelling.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If your class is keeping a word wall, then have a student write the vocabulary word and definition down on a piece of paper and add it to the word wall."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0d905348-7fe9-46b5-a512-06b65d7eaab6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "770ec6d6-5159-43eb-a208-a0234dc6466a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6078f46e-137f-401a-bcbd-0aca6bc2d87d",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6078f46e-137f-401a-bcbd-0aca6bc2d87d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "770ec6d6-5159-43eb-a208-a0234dc6466a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "36525a7c-fb43-4a7f-95c6-899eca04ef35",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce expository data stories and the Spotify Year Wrapped example.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Place students in pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each pair a copy of the Data Storytelling activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:**Direct students to Levels 1 and 2 to complete the Expository Data Story section of the Data Storytelling activity guide.\n- **Level 1**: This provides students with a visual representation of the Spotify Year Wrapped cards. These are interesting visualizations that are based on users' real data.\n- **Level 2**: Students use AI Chat to assist with analyzing the existing cards or authoring their own unique Spotify data card.",
        "progression_name": "Expository Data Story"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "36525a7c-fb43-4a7f-95c6-899eca04ef35",
        "lesson_activity.key": "770ec6d6-5159-43eb-a208-a0234dc6466a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "43318ab7-c63f-4e63-85f8-abe5ad749efd",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Help students who might not have heard of Spotify or who aren’t familiar with music streaming services by making the comparison to a streaming service that they might know (YouTube, Netflix, etc). Press the students to come up with attributes for the cards that go beyond the obvious. Students might be tempted to find one attribute and stop; however, as seen in the example above, there are often many different possibilities. Some ideas to explore for those students who might be creatively blocked on this portion of the assignment include:\n* Cards based on favorite genres of music (country, musicals, jazz, R&B, rock, and hip hop)\n* Cards based on the time of day during which music is most often streamed\n* Cards based on how many different languages are present in the songs being streamed\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What is your data story idea for a Spotify \"Year Wrapped\" card? What data attribute(s) is it based on?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** As students share, emphasize how the students’ expository data story relates to the attributes that they identify. You could also open it up for discussion for the class to provide additional expository details or attributes. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If you have extra time, an extension to this activity might be to have students actually create the card themselves in Google Slides. They could use an AI art generator, if they have access to one, to create a cover image for the card, similar to how Spotify’s cards are laid out. On the front of the card, in addition to the description of the user who earns the card, they can also list out the attributes necessary to consider. Printing these and hanging them on the wall could make an engaging anchor chart to reinforce how data can be used to tell interesting and insightful stories about people."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "43318ab7-c63f-4e63-85f8-abe5ad749efd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "770ec6d6-5159-43eb-a208-a0234dc6466a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7d521d80-91d5-4f11-bcde-c25606245473",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7d521d80-91d5-4f11-bcde-c25606245473",
        "lesson_activity.key": "770ec6d6-5159-43eb-a208-a0234dc6466a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "655df60b-4673-4c38-a5db-33d7e69f9a99",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce persuasive data stories and the example.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:**  Direct students to Levels 3 - 4 to complete the Persuasive Data Story section of the Data Storytelling activity guide.\n- **Level 3**: This provides students with an infographic of Lebron James career statistics. \n- **Level 4**: Students use AI Chat to assist with adding an emotional angle as well as analyzing the infographic for misleading or biased information.",
        "progression_name": "Persuasive Data Story"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "655df60b-4673-4c38-a5db-33d7e69f9a99",
        "lesson_activity.key": "770ec6d6-5159-43eb-a208-a0234dc6466a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "35cab12c-4815-4dee-8919-274d1d7752df",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce AI-Generated infographic\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What makes this convincing (or not)? Would you trust a story generated by AI? Why or why not?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to separate out statistics that seem trustworthy and those that seem questionable. They should be curious about where the information came from and what potential bias or inaccuracies AI-generated infographics contain.\n\n\n\n\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "35cab12c-4815-4dee-8919-274d1d7752df",
        "lesson_activity.key": "770ec6d6-5159-43eb-a208-a0234dc6466a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d42aadd2-11c8-4083-b5e2-39845b38bab5",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 5 to choose one of the three party planning datasets and create a persuasive data story that helps guide the party planners to make a decision.\n- **Level 5**: A choice level that provides three different datasets on which students will create their own persuasive data story.\n- **Level 6**: Students use AI Chat to assist with creating a persuasive data story.\n",
        "progression_name": "Party Planning Datasets"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d42aadd2-11c8-4083-b5e2-39845b38bab5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "770ec6d6-5159-43eb-a208-a0234dc6466a"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2cc8558b-fb2b-4aa4-be07-3947fbc52759",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2cc8558b-fb2b-4aa4-be07-3947fbc52759",
        "lesson_activity.key": "45563d69-98ea-4139-8f44-612d4e7dcc9e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "228e9a3b-35e4-44c2-8bd4-33301e4aa7b2",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Chart Match Questions activity guide.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Briefly explain that students will explore visualizations based on fictional Spotify data and that each chart is designed to answer a specific question. Emphasize that a data visualization is a graphical representation of information and data.\n",
        "progression_name": "Data Talk"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "228e9a3b-35e4-44c2-8bd4-33301e4aa7b2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1a84b6a9-d190-4f50-bad6-739f65702912"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bd514b18-9d87-49aa-ad6b-3bc44d57cf08",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to begin walking around the room to match each question on their guide to a visualization. Remind them to write down why they made that match and anything they notice or wonder about the chart.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for students discussing reasoning with their partners. Ask probing questions like, “What in the chart made you pick this one for your question?” or “What’s something interesting you noticed?”",
        "progression_name": "Shape of Distribution",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Consider modeling one match as a think-aloud before students begin. This helps students understand the type of connections they should make between questions and visuals."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bd514b18-9d87-49aa-ad6b-3bc44d57cf08",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1a84b6a9-d190-4f50-bad6-739f65702912"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "30263706-9356-42b3-8a27-5be7504593fd",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "30263706-9356-42b3-8a27-5be7504593fd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1a84b6a9-d190-4f50-bad6-739f65702912"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d19edd71-eef6-4ac7-9c84-d01756d21805",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the term data visualizations and explain that these visuals help us spot patterns and trends more quickly than reading rows of numbers. Direct students to fill in their Unit Guide"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d19edd71-eef6-4ac7-9c84-d01756d21805",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c4e117f9-7d95-40a6-8918-eace38e9e754",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce bar charts. Explain that bar charts are one of the most common ways to visualize data. They help us compare quantities across different categories.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Tell students to watch for the steps they’ll use in their own charts as they watch the brief video— especially how to select data and choose a chart type.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the video \"*How to Make a Chart in Google Sheets*\"\n\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c4e117f9-7d95-40a6-8918-eace38e9e754",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4ec7b995-a276-4b57-88f7-4f1da83be693",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 7, Levels 1 - 2. \n* **Level 1:** Students review bar chart basics. \n* **Level 2:** Students use Google Sheets to make a unique bar chart using the school pizza party dataset.",
        "progression_name": "Creating Bar Charts"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4ec7b995-a276-4b57-88f7-4f1da83be693",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "334b330b-fcb9-400f-8575-f673f44da251",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check that students understand how to select the correct column for charting. Ask, “What question are you trying to answer with this chart?” Listen for students identifying unexpected findings. Encourage them to think about what the chart tells them that a table of numbers would not.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to title their chart clearly and check that axis labels make sense. Provide feedback on this as you circulate.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "334b330b-fcb9-400f-8575-f673f44da251",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "812456c9-c967-4b5f-83c6-a3e79c54d72a",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** What did the bar chart help you notice about the data?\n\n- Turn and Talk\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should recognize that bar charts make it easier to compare categories (e.g., favorite pizza types, number of friends). Students may learn what the most and least popular pizza topping is, or the most common music preference, etc. \n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Consider jotting down a couple strong student observations on the board to model good insight."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "812456c9-c967-4b5f-83c6-a3e79c54d72a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d21d35b0-e0e5-4d19-ac54-fef79e11a984",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce pie charts. Explain that pie charts show how a whole is broken into parts. They're good for understanding proportions, but less precise than bar charts when comparing exact counts.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the video \"*Create a Pie Chart in Google Sheets*\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 7, Levels 3 - 4. \n* **Level 3:** Students review how to make pie charts.  \n* **Level 4:** Students use Google Sheets to make a unique pie chart using the school pizza party dataset.",
        "progression_name": "Creating Pie Charts"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d21d35b0-e0e5-4d19-ac54-fef79e11a984",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "29a4a271-ea2d-44ab-8fbd-ee78f73346e4",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ask students what question they are trying to answer with their pie chart. Check that their chart categories make up a whole (e.g., types of pizza, not individual soda amounts).\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to choose a column with repeated categories (like \"What kind of pizza do you like best?\") so that the pie chart groups values into meaningful slices. If students are unsure, suggest they look for columns with text answers that repeat often — these work best for pie charts.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "29a4a271-ea2d-44ab-8fbd-ee78f73346e4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5a0859e9-c745-43aa-b28f-4c213d87403d",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** What are the similarities and differences between a bar chart and a pie chart?\n- Think - Pair - Share\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should understand that both charts show categorical data. Bar charts are better for comparing exact values across categories, while pie charts show relative proportions of a whole. Example responses: “Bar charts make it easier to see the biggest and smallest categories,” or “Pie charts are helpful for seeing how the total is divided.”\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "You could create a quick side-by-side chart comparison with the same data on the board to reinforce differences."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5a0859e9-c745-43aa-b28f-4c213d87403d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "62bc1b7a-32d1-4ee5-86a2-0004c1d43203",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the video \"*How to Use Filters in Google Sheets*\""
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "62bc1b7a-32d1-4ee5-86a2-0004c1d43203",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "05f714d4-6362-4d7c-9668-150a8ff12dc3",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Sometimes we want to focus on certain aspects of our dataset instead of visualizing everything. We can do this using a filter.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "05f714d4-6362-4d7c-9668-150a8ff12dc3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0fb74be6-7714-476d-981e-b93eff5c8461",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce filter as a tool to focus on just part of the dataset — like seeing what only 7th graders think or what songs a certain group prefers.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Ask students to share examples of times they’ve “filtered” something in real life (e.g., Netflix genres, online shopping, playlists).\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0fb74be6-7714-476d-981e-b93eff5c8461",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "845aff66-eefc-48e0-8689-5b736dd7b58d",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Imagine you're planning a pizza party. How might filtering the data by grade or party personality change your decisions about music, food, or activities?",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "845aff66-eefc-48e0-8689-5b736dd7b58d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5245e772-1b72-413a-bf04-130c96f2f230",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** How might filtering the data by grade level or personality type change your party planning choices?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should identify how different groups might prefer different songs, pizza types, or party durations. Example: “7th graders might want quieter music” or “Social Butterflies invite more friends.”"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5245e772-1b72-413a-bf04-130c96f2f230",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f7e0fe62-ec2e-41d1-8478-537031dd57c6",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 7, Levels 5 - 6.\n* **Level 5:** Students review the basics of applying filters. \n* **Level 6:** Students use Google Sheets to apply filters and to make visualizations using the school pizza party dataset.\n",
        "progression_name": "Applying Filters",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students who finish early, to use their filtering and data visualization skills to create a new chart in the Google Sheet. Direct them to the tab called Optional Extension to answer a question of their choice or one of the questions listed."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f7e0fe62-ec2e-41d1-8478-537031dd57c6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "44729d84-e571-49ec-a846-de3af552ceb9",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ask students what group they filtered by and what changed in the chart compared to the unfiltered version. Encourage students to try multiple filters and compare — what changes when you filter for Performers vs. Relaxers?   \n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "44729d84-e571-49ec-a846-de3af552ceb9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "def059bd-8561-438b-acf7-e98bf75f0044",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to screenshot one of their charts in order to upload it to the AI Assistant for feedback.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 7 in order to get AI-assisted feedback on one of their visualizations. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Assist students with snipping, screenshotting, or saving an image of one of the charts that they have created. They might also need assistance with uploading this image into the AI Chat.\n",
        "progression_name": "AI Chat: Data Visualizations"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "def059bd-8561-438b-acf7-e98bf75f0044",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "dc3933e4-f519-4daa-9b21-c6b1a405fa9c",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students aren’t sure what to ask the AI, suggest something like, “How can I make this chart easier to understand?”"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "dc3933e4-f519-4daa-9b21-c6b1a405fa9c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "562f8566-c95f-492f-b264-402dbaa43c44",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students revise their original chart using the feedback they received.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 8 to upload a revised visualization and complete a reflection.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Look for charts with clear improvements — updated titles, better axis labels, changed chart types — and ask students to explain what they changed and why.\n",
        "progression_name": "AI Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "562f8566-c95f-492f-b264-402dbaa43c44",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "79c5c632-38ea-4ded-a381-2ebb4e0f6e03",
      "position": 19,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Use the revised chart and student reflection as a formative check of their understanding of chart creation, appropriate chart selection, and clarity of communication. If students struggle with labeling or chart choice, revisit slides on chart types (Slides 10 and 14) and allow time for more practice in Levels 2–4"
          },
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Use the revised chart and student reflection as a formative check of their understanding of chart creation, appropriate chart selection, and clarity of communication. If students struggle with labeling or chart choice, revisit slides on chart types (Slides 10 and 14) and allow time for more practice in Levels 2–4"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "79c5c632-38ea-4ded-a381-2ebb4e0f6e03",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f662f1fb-6701-47f9-88f9-616c2fc0a9d7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4eb0fe2e-dd9b-4945-94fd-d58406a97aa6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4eb0fe2e-dd9b-4945-94fd-d58406a97aa6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "44c4cee5-1a8f-4c07-a21b-c26ca6bab8e1"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "baf3e411-f476-4c2d-b6a2-54d1b2879403",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Group students into pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 1 to complete a Data Talk with their partner on the dataset. Students write what they notice and what they wonder about the visualization. After students have had a chance to write a couple things they noticed and wondered, instruct students to share with their partner. Give students a few minutes to share before bringing the class back together.",
        "progression_name": "Data Talk"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "baf3e411-f476-4c2d-b6a2-54d1b2879403",
        "lesson_activity.key": "98ec45e1-83ba-4adb-81cb-f0bd19521475"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9a677bf8-4e88-4dc1-9e51-ebb98794ae01",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Open Level 1 and show the student responses to the class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Let's take a look at what you noticed and wondered. What common themes do we see in our responses?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** As students share what they notice and what they wonder about the dataset, highlight any responses that refer to outliers, patterns, or trends, even if they don’t use those terms explicitly.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "After students have had a chance to record their responses in the level and share with their partner, the teacher asks several students to share things they noticed and things they wondered. Student responses can also be displayed for the class to help drive the conversation. \n\nUsually, the teacher steers the conversation to wondering about something that the class is about to focus on, which in this case is outliers, patterns and trends. In a Data Talk the teacher does not have to be an expert in the topic of data visualization - if a student asks a question, you can say that you do not know the answer, but would love to find out together! This is a nice opportunity to model not knowing, and embracing uncertainty. \n\nThe purpose of a Data Talk  is to make an opening task accessible to all students with these two approachable questions. By thinking about them and responding, students gain entry into the context and might get their curiosity piqued."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9a677bf8-4e88-4dc1-9e51-ebb98794ae01",
        "lesson_activity.key": "98ec45e1-83ba-4adb-81cb-f0bd19521475"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "71ebfc6f-1e0b-44db-ab2c-945fd40edb0e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "71ebfc6f-1e0b-44db-ab2c-945fd40edb0e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "98ec45e1-83ba-4adb-81cb-f0bd19521475"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ed3465a0-dd5c-4dd3-938b-1566e22a38c9",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which of these makes it easier for a human to decide when the party should be? Why?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Based on how the Data Talk went, this may be a very quick discussion. The point here is to make it clear, if it isn’t already, that the bottom graph provides much more useful information for someone who is trying to make a decision.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ed3465a0-dd5c-4dd3-938b-1566e22a38c9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "98ec45e1-83ba-4adb-81cb-f0bd19521475"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "da787a85-1c8c-4cd2-929f-255e8a4c8ba4",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the pizza party topping problem.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Is this data useful?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should highlight issues with this data that make it less useful, such as the comments that are not related to pizza toppings and the duplicate responses. If no one mentions it, point out that this data looks a lot like one of the graphs they saw in the warm up, where there isn’t a very clear pattern. Tell students that data scientists call data like this \"raw data\" or \"messy data\".\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain to the students that the data needs to be cleaned to make it more usable and ways that data scientists do this.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have a student add data cleaning to the Word Wall.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "You may want to model how they can do this by copying and pasting or carefully typing into the \"Clean Data\" column."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "da787a85-1c8c-4cd2-929f-255e8a4c8ba4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cc4930a0-60be-4b07-b95b-9063dd595642",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cc4930a0-60be-4b07-b95b-9063dd595642",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "69157238-bb1e-43b4-acc3-9c8fd2c8be1a",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students use the panels in Level 2 to review how to copy and clean a dataset.",
        "progression_name": "Cleaning Data Panel"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "69157238-bb1e-43b4-acc3-9c8fd2c8be1a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6fd51ec7-b7ef-4f1b-b9c8-ad95b8f2859a",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6fd51ec7-b7ef-4f1b-b9c8-ad95b8f2859a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "00cfdee4-1b19-4bc7-aade-07fbe406803e",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 3. For each entry in the first column, students should decide if they want to keep it the same, delete it, or change it.",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "00cfdee4-1b19-4bc7-aade-07fbe406803e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3fe2882e-aad5-40ee-91a8-5b90fef52d9c",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3fe2882e-aad5-40ee-91a8-5b90fef52d9c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d4d5965f-f02e-4168-b5d4-394cff396974",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Walk around the classroom and prompt students to make a new graph of the \"Clean Data\" column once they are done.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Group students into pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have pairs engage in the Compare and Connect protocol using the dataset they just cleaned.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "A key idea is Data Science is that information can be represented in a variety of ways; data scientists have to make choices, and these choices have trade-offs. When students compare their work, they have an opportunity to both communicate the choices they made and to see the choices made by another student. When they connect back to the source of information - whether it be a primary source or a data set - students are pushed to consider what information is represented in their work, and what information is not."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d4d5965f-f02e-4168-b5d4-394cff396974",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "da8b4002-6f95-412e-affd-f377819ce502",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "da8b4002-6f95-412e-affd-f377819ce502",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8f01e80a-f940-4250-9259-63adbab56a95",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "You’ve seen how you and your partner cleaned messy data entries. Now let’s bring in AI as a third voice. How would it clean a given messy data entry and do you agree with it?",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8f01e80a-f940-4250-9259-63adbab56a95",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "38742517-6932-4f6b-bfb5-51a76e0fff30",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 4 and ask AI Chat how it would clean a given messy entry. Then compare and discuss its answer with a partner.",
        "progression_name": "Ask AI for Cleaning Tips"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "38742517-6932-4f6b-bfb5-51a76e0fff30",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a68cab27-c570-47f8-bf0a-0a6c7b04f8a1",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a68cab27-c570-47f8-bf0a-0a6c7b04f8a1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b86cd471-6e0e-4f00-9203-2de63d34268c",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which approach feels more accurate or respectful?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Student answers will vary. Students might say revising the entry preserves the intent, while deleting it removes a valid opinion. The goal is for students to recognize that respectful data cleaning means balancing clarity with the original meaning of the response.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What assumptions did AI make that you didn’t?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Student answers will vary. The goal is to prompt students to reflect on how AI may have interpreted the tone, intent, or meaning differently than they did.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b86cd471-6e0e-4f00-9203-2de63d34268c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d0a68c4f-5f12-4bbc-82a3-acd0907c5161",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which do you think should be prioritized when deciding how to clean data?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This discussion is a chance for the class to wrestle with the ambiguities that come up when cleaning data , (i.e. how valuable information can get lost when cleaning the data to make it more usable by computers and readable by people.) "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d0a68c4f-5f12-4bbc-82a3-acd0907c5161",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "632128a6-55fb-49ed-bab9-65017d0e40b5",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Remind students of the ethical framework introduced in Lesson 3.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which do you think should be prioritized when deciding how to clean data?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** This discussion is a chance for the class to wrestle with the ambiguities that come up when cleaning data , (i.e. how valuable information can get lost when cleaning the data to make it more usable by computers and readable by people.) \n\nFor Accuracy and Bias, students may bring up things like:\n* Changing the format allows the cleaners bias to enter the picture\n* Cleaned data is not accurately what the person wanted\n* Cleaned Data helps form a more accurate picture -- someone who misspelled pepperoni still wants pepperoni pizza\n\nFor Privacy, students may bring up things like:\n* Creating categories can unintentionally identify certain members of a group\n\nFor Misuse and Consent, students may bring up things like:\n* It’s possible that people have not consented to their data being used in this altered, cleaned, format",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Push the discussion further by asking some of the following:\n* *Did all of your graphs of the clean data look the same?*\n* *What are some things data scientists think about when they're cleaning data?*\n* *Is there any important data that got left out of the new clean data set?*\n* *Ask students what they did with the response, \"I’m allergic to mushrooms.\"*"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "632128a6-55fb-49ed-bab9-65017d0e40b5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ab63d364-c443-4307-90a8-de248a1a839b",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Explain that there are real world implications of data cleaning. In the 2000 US Presidential election, the margin of votes between Al Gore and George W. Bush in Florida was less than half a percent, which triggered a manual recount of votes. During the manual recount, several inconsistencies were noted. Ballots in Duval County had more \"overvotes\" than usual, likely due to instructions that stated “Vote every page\". As a result, 21,000 ballots had multiple markings, such as two or more choices for president. In Palm Beach County, Pat Buchanan had four times as many votes from people who voted in person using the Butterfly ballot (pictured above) as people in the county who voted absentee using non-butterfly ballots. In Duval County, data cleaning meant throwing out overvoted ballots. In Palm Beach County, data cleaning meant recording all votes cast for Pat Buchanan (even if they were cast incorrectly).\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ab63d364-c443-4307-90a8-de248a1a839b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ee8a63a8-2442-4527-9d4d-af249e82d3f2",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ee8a63a8-2442-4527-9d4d-af249e82d3f2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fedb0b4f-8773-4b85-bab0-183aec166ed4",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Synthesize the discussion by having students help you summarize ideas about the following on an anchor chart:\n* How data scientists clean data\n* Important considerations for cleaning data",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Refer to the Anchor Charts in Data Science for an example of what this might look like once it’s filled in."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fedb0b4f-8773-4b85-bab0-183aec166ed4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cf096628-2842-42a8-9ddc-efc8b8525eb2",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** What are the advantages and disadvantages of each question type?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to explain that free response questions allow surveyed users to express a wider variety of choices but may require more data cleaning on the part of the data scientist. Closed questions, e.g. radio selection or dropdowns, provide data that doesn’t need to be cleaned but they also don’t provide users with as much choice. In the next part of the lesson, students will look at data visualizations that result from the closed question “What score did each student receive?”"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cf096628-2842-42a8-9ddc-efc8b8525eb2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "eaf5f705-5087-420f-aef3-3f68c3fe1b09",
      "position": 19,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "eaf5f705-5087-420f-aef3-3f68c3fe1b09",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a4a5bbed-cdeb-4aed-9123-151ee3f4245f",
      "position": 20,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce shape of distribution.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce bell curve.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce skewed distribution.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce skewed distribution.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the shape of distribution sentence starters.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which sentence starter would you use to describe the shape of distribution for this chart?*\n\n* Give students a moment to think about their response before they share with a partner and then with the class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** For the provided dot plot, most of the sentence starters in the word bank will work. Guide students to effectively use the sentence starters to describe and discuss the shape of a data distribution. The goal is to help them learn how to accurately apply these phrases when analyzing and communicating about the distribution patterns observed in charts, enhancing their ability to articulate data insights clearly and correctly.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce measures of center.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the measures of center sentence starters.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which sentence starter would you use to describe the measures of center for this chart?*\n\n* Give students a moment to think about their response before they share with a partner and then with the class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Encourage students to accurately utilize the provided sentence starters to identify and discuss measures of center such as the mean, median, and mode, based on the data distribution shown in the chart."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a4a5bbed-cdeb-4aed-9123-151ee3f4245f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "92bfba45-c93a-4549-908e-515e5a05b27e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a21dd640-3aff-41a1-a07f-cf636bb4c23d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "his way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a21dd640-3aff-41a1-a07f-cf636bb4c23d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d77da750-dba0-41e3-8a7c-ff6e717dcf6f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fe78eada-d8f3-4b94-8e3f-efd7fe879388",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Group students into pairs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 1 to complete a Data Talk with their partner on the Dessert dataset. Students write what they notice and what they wonder about the visualization. After students have had a chance to write a couple things they noticed and wondered, instruct students to share with their partner. Give students a few minutes to share before bringing the class back together.",
        "progression_name": "Data Talk"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fe78eada-d8f3-4b94-8e3f-efd7fe879388",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e79c6183-3345-45ef-93c7-5d78f4709db5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c1661d95-b321-4dbc-ac62-2fa02eb0cd67",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Open Level 1 and show the student responses to the class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Let's take a look at what you noticed and wondered. What common themes do we see in our responses?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** As students share what they notice and what they wonder about the Dessert dataset, highlight any responses that refer to outliers, patterns, or trends, even if they don’t use those terms explicitly. Steer the discussion and student wonderings to focus on the following:\n\n* Outliers:\n   * **Pumpkin Pie in November:** The sharp increase in pumpkin pie consumption in November is an outlier. This suggests that pumpkin pie is highly favored during Thanksgiving and should be a priority dessert for November school events.\n   * **Low Dessert Consumption in January:** There is a noticeable drop in all dessert types in January, likely due to a post-holiday decrease in interest or health-driven New Year resolutions. This could imply that January school parties might focus less on desserts or offer healthier dessert options.\n\n* Patterns:\n   * **Summer Preference for Ice Cream:** Ice cream shows increased consumption during the summer months (June, July, August). This indicates a preference for cooler, refreshing desserts during warmer weather, making it an ideal choice for end-of-year or summer-related school celebrations.\n\n* Trends:\n   * **Rising Cookie Consumption in Spring and Summer:** There is an upward trend in cookie consumption from March to July, peaking in July. This could indicate a growing preference for cookies during this period, possibly due to their convenience at events or their appeal to a broad range of students.\n\n* Insights:\n   * **Seasonal Preferences:** Different desserts are favored at different times of the year. Tailoring dessert offerings to seasonal preferences could enhance student enjoyment and participation in school parties."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c1661d95-b321-4dbc-ac62-2fa02eb0cd67",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e79c6183-3345-45ef-93c7-5d78f4709db5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "35781642-3e86-49d1-8ca8-8f1a7f524458",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "35781642-3e86-49d1-8ca8-8f1a7f524458",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e79c6183-3345-45ef-93c7-5d78f4709db5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4706808d-be5e-4164-8456-dc47b18e32e3",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have a student to add the terms outlier, pattern, and trend to the Word Wall.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to take a moment and decide on one of the answer options for this quick self-check of what trends in data do for us\n* Trends provide insights into the overall direction and momentum, helping in strategic planning and long-term predictions.\n* Trends are typically observed as a consistent upward or downward slope in line graphs or moving averages that smooth out fluctuations to highlight the general direction of the data."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4706808d-be5e-4164-8456-dc47b18e32e3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e79c6183-3345-45ef-93c7-5d78f4709db5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c38c405b-22d1-4f97-89ad-a4a834c2ff85",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c38c405b-22d1-4f97-89ad-a4a834c2ff85",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e79c6183-3345-45ef-93c7-5d78f4709db5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cc0e1d46-3ca9-46bd-b318-7ae9a0322bc9",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to take a moment and decide on one of the answer options for this quick self-check of what outliers in data do for us.\n* Outliers can sometimes distort the understanding of trends and patterns if not appropriately handled. * They might indicate either errors to be corrected or special cases that need separate investigation.\n* Outliers might appear as points that break away from the cluster or main grouping of data in scatter plots, bar charts, or line graphs.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to take a moment and decide on one of the answer options for this quick self-check of what patterns in data do for us\n* Patterns help in understanding the regular behavior or characteristics within data, which is useful for tasks like anomaly detection, where deviations from these patterns become evident.\n* Patterns are often visible through repeated shapes or configurations in the data, such as recurring cycles in a line graph or consistent groupings in scatter plots.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cc0e1d46-3ca9-46bd-b318-7ae9a0322bc9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e79c6183-3345-45ef-93c7-5d78f4709db5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0df6bdc8-078d-4292-a7b4-4d7c37af803e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Group students into pairs in order to work through the interpretation of the four datasets present on Level 2.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the accompanying Data Interpretations activity guide for their assigned dataset. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0df6bdc8-078d-4292-a7b4-4d7c37af803e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1753038-4448-455a-b918-2337d20bbe98"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cec72087-1128-4495-9439-a08b68342ae7",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The activity guide can be collected at the end of the lesson as a way to formatively assess students ability to create a visual representation and answer questions about a dataset."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cec72087-1128-4495-9439-a08b68342ae7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1753038-4448-455a-b918-2337d20bbe98"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a90baffe-3460-4a99-979e-6b54a1b11ab7",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 2. Students should work with their partner, following the instructions to explore each dataset and visualization. Then discuss and answer the questions with their partner.",
        "progression_name": "Data Interpretation"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a90baffe-3460-4a99-979e-6b54a1b11ab7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1753038-4448-455a-b918-2337d20bbe98"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "64f129a4-dc5d-4ccd-8550-141b6738d1a5",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "64f129a4-dc5d-4ccd-8550-141b6738d1a5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1753038-4448-455a-b918-2337d20bbe98"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "852c58c3-2c19-4a13-9e81-448e300268eb",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As you move around the room, ensure that students are reviewing the visualizations. Prompt students to go beyond simple observations by asking probing questions that encourage them to think about the \"why\" and \"how\" behind the data outliers, patterns, and trends they observe. Ensure that both students in each pair are engaged and contributing to the discussions.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students should spend no more than twenty minutes on Part 1, roughly five minutes per level. It might be helpful to display a timer or to announce to students where they should be in the process of completing Part 1. For example, after about two minutes of reviewing the data and visualization let students know that they should be answering the questions. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "852c58c3-2c19-4a13-9e81-448e300268eb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1753038-4448-455a-b918-2337d20bbe98"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "41d6a504-f36a-4f42-b622-80ed2c58fbaa",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** As a group, have students discuss their data interpretations and observations from the activity.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As students share and discuss in their groups, circulate to ensure they are engaging in meaningful discussions and staying on task. Prompt students to delve deeper during both analysis and group discussions, ensuring they explore beyond surface level observations. For those groups who might need the additional assistance, guide them to consider the implications of their findings not just on Micah’s habits but as a reflection of broader data analysis challenges\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to complete Level 3.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students to work together to create an Expository Data Story that explains Micah’s cleaning habits over time. Students should keep it short and to the point, ensuring that their decisions are based on their datasets. Give students the option to write their data story in the free response box in Level 3 or use a different medium and upload a picture of it.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** As you move around the room, ensure students integrate their insights from all four datasets to form a coherent story. Encourage them to go beyond surface-level descriptions by having them consider underlying causes and broader implications. .",
        "progression_name": "Expository Data Story",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "The Data Interpretation activity guide can be collected and used as a formative assessment of student learning."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "41d6a504-f36a-4f42-b622-80ed2c58fbaa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1753038-4448-455a-b918-2337d20bbe98"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "23418f89-ad46-49ec-bed7-11d4753b3062",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have one person from each group share a highlight from their group’s data story with the class.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** What commonalities and differences do we see in the different expository data stories? What are the ethical implications of presenting the same data in different ways?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to identify common themes and patterns across data stories. They should also be able to identify differences in how they presented the data. Have students consider the different conclusions one could draw from presenting the data in different ways.\n",
        "progression_name": "Expository Data Story"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "23418f89-ad46-49ec-bed7-11d4753b3062",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1753038-4448-455a-b918-2337d20bbe98"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6d3c73a4-5849-4de9-bbb1-c9d91e61c082",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to complete Level 4\n* Students practice identifying trends, patterns, and outliers in a data visualization.\n",
        "progression_name": "Check for Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6d3c73a4-5849-4de9-bbb1-c9d91e61c082",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e1753038-4448-455a-b918-2337d20bbe98"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "9615767f-be3f-4022-9108-dddcabe740bd",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "9615767f-be3f-4022-9108-dddcabe740bd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b9a15ef0-28e9-406b-860e-1664657ffbe7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e67aa0ed-a897-4da0-8e8e-d0e00ad62a64",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 1 to analyze a provided histogram using the Roller Coaster dataset. Students should then move on to Levels 2, 3, and 4 to answer the questions about the context, shape of distribution and measures of center about the histogram. Finally, have students compare with a neighbor.",
        "progression_name": "Roller Coasters"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e67aa0ed-a897-4da0-8e8e-d0e00ad62a64",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b7d8a51-4f96-4da8-8957-3a70980b03c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7856122b-cc20-489a-a356-ec8c6465a9c2",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How did you describe the context for this graph?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Guide students to effectively use the sentence starters to describe and discuss the context. The goal is to help them learn how to accurately apply these phrases when communicating about the context, enhancing their ability to articulate data insights clearly and correctly.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Consider displaying students' responses from the level to show different ways to analyze the data using the word bank. This approach will let students learn from each other and understand various ways to explain the context of data."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7856122b-cc20-489a-a356-ec8c6465a9c2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b7d8a51-4f96-4da8-8957-3a70980b03c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b8204c40-c086-4f4e-9faf-4ef008b3482b",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b8204c40-c086-4f4e-9faf-4ef008b3482b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b7d8a51-4f96-4da8-8957-3a70980b03c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fc2fcaa6-6782-4b0e-a639-6433caaa5acc",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How did you describe the shape of distribution for this graph?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Guide students to effectively use the sentence starters to describe and discuss the shape of distribution. The goal is to help them learn how to accurately apply these phrases when analyzing and communicating about the shape of distribution, enhancing their ability to articulate data insights clearly and correctly.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Consider displaying students' responses from the level to show different ways to analyze the data using the word bank. This approach will let students learn from each other and understand various ways to explain the shape of distribution of the data."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fc2fcaa6-6782-4b0e-a639-6433caaa5acc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b7d8a51-4f96-4da8-8957-3a70980b03c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e8473e53-dfe1-48e1-8a6e-5201e5f30d5d",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How did you describe the measures of center for this graph?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Guide students to effectively use the sentence starters to describe and discuss the measures of center. The goal is to help them learn how to accurately apply these phrases when analyzing and communicating about the measures of center, enhancing their ability to articulate data insights clearly and correctly.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Consider displaying students' responses from the level to show different ways to analyze the data using the word bank. This approach will let students learn from each other and understand various ways to explain the measures of center of the data."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e8473e53-dfe1-48e1-8a6e-5201e5f30d5d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b7d8a51-4f96-4da8-8957-3a70980b03c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "66c71ccc-b50a-41fa-bf03-a921ac66f6c6",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the Question of the Day."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "66c71ccc-b50a-41fa-bf03-a921ac66f6c6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0b7d8a51-4f96-4da8-8957-3a70980b03c7"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cc6d6c2b-3596-4f7c-8bed-ff26fa9d317b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce **histograms**. Explain that histograms condense a data into an easily interpreted visual by taking many data points and grouping them into logical ranges or bins similar in appearance to a bar graph.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Tell students to watch for the steps they’ll use to create their own histogram.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the video \"*How to Create a Histogram in Google Sheets*\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 7, Levels 5-6.\n* **Level 5:** Students review the basics of histogram creation.\n* **Level 6:** Students use Google Sheets to create histograms for the top speed of both steel and wood rollercoasters.",
        "progression_name": "Creating Histograms"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cc6d6c2b-3596-4f7c-8bed-ff26fa9d317b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b533a95b-12cb-4b80-b189-f864db677aa9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "059a327b-3aa3-48d1-88e4-d18135fb66c0",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "059a327b-3aa3-48d1-88e4-d18135fb66c0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b533a95b-12cb-4b80-b189-f864db677aa9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "38b7ca79-6570-4e08-b95a-afb78562b56e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check that students understand how to select the correct column for charting. Ask, “What question are you trying to answer with this chart?” Listen for students identifying unexpected findings.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to title their chart clearly and check that axis labels make sense. Provide feedback on this as you circulate."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "38b7ca79-6570-4e08-b95a-afb78562b56e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b533a95b-12cb-4b80-b189-f864db677aa9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ec92808a-bba5-4f39-b4a6-4c48ea537b67",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** How could changing the bin size of a histogram change someone’s interpretation of the data?\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Guide students to describe and discuss the different shapes of distribution. The goal is for them to understand that different bin sizes can lead people to different conclusions. Larger bin sizes might obscure information such as a bimodal distribution, whereas smaller bin sizes might make it harder to draw conclusions about the data.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Click to show the illustration if students are stuck. If students struggle to come up with a response, ask them what assumptions they might make if they only saw the histogram on the left. Then ask how making more bins of smaller size added additional information."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ec92808a-bba5-4f39-b4a6-4c48ea537b67",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b533a95b-12cb-4b80-b189-f864db677aa9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "37bdd01e-52c4-4fd4-8acb-78a5144eaf26",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce **scatter plot**. Explain that scatter plots are data visualizations that use dots to represent the values of two different variables, whose values are plotted along the X and Y axis.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Tell students to watch for the steps they’ll use to create their own scatter plots\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-video-camera\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Video:** Show the video \"*How to Make a Scatter Plot in Google Sheets*\"\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 7, Levels 7-8. \n* **Level 7:** Students review the basics of scatter plot creation.\n* **Level 8:** Students use Google Sheets to create scatter plots which answer several data questions.",
        "progression_name": "Creating Scatterplots"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "37bdd01e-52c4-4fd4-8acb-78a5144eaf26",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b533a95b-12cb-4b80-b189-f864db677aa9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8b8bd5dc-f0b8-417b-bda5-9c249515b10e",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check that students understand how to select the correct columns for charting. Ask, “What two variables are you trying to compare?” Listen for students identifying unexpected findings. Make sure that the students are using numerical values for the best outcome in Sheets\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8b8bd5dc-f0b8-417b-bda5-9c249515b10e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b533a95b-12cb-4b80-b189-f864db677aa9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e80673e2-40c7-4609-af8b-f50009163ed7",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Introduce the concept of **spreadsheet formulas**. Explain that spreadsheets often have functions that you can use in order to quickly summarize and analyze data attributes and cases.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Lesson 7, Levels 9-10. \n* **Level 9:** Students review how to use formulas in a spreadsheet.\n* **Level 10:** Students utilize formulas to summarize data statistics.",
        "progression_name": "Using Formulas with Datasets"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e80673e2-40c7-4609-af8b-f50009163ed7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b533a95b-12cb-4b80-b189-f864db677aa9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "10f04a42-18c1-4633-a435-a406d0ef2516",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check that students understand how to use formulas within cells. Make sure that they understand how to select a range of data. Check if students understand how to apply the new techniques in Google Sheets. Ensure they are not just following steps mechanically but are grasping why they are using specific features for their visualizations."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "10f04a42-18c1-4633-a435-a406d0ef2516",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b533a95b-12cb-4b80-b189-f864db677aa9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d8c05369-f6dd-492a-a99c-1bfa6f55d14d",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to complete at least two of the choices on Level 11. Students may complete more than two if they have time.",
        "progression_name": "Independent Practice"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d8c05369-f6dd-492a-a99c-1bfa6f55d14d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b533a95b-12cb-4b80-b189-f864db677aa9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2edb9539-c881-405d-806e-2de6ace68585",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Check if students understand how to apply the new techniques in Google Sheets. Ensure they are not just following steps mechanically but are grasping why they are using specific features for their visualizations.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2edb9539-c881-405d-806e-2de6ace68585",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b533a95b-12cb-4b80-b189-f864db677aa9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1a18a662-dbd4-4c9e-a101-83487f9b8377",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Remind students of the ethical framework introduced in Lesson 3.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What are some additional ethical concerns we should keep in mind when using the visualization tools and techniques we learned today?*\n\n* Use a Think/Pair/Share and call on students to provide their responses.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to identify and articulate potential ethical issues arising from the use of data visualization tools, such as bias and misinformation. They should also be able to suggest responsible practices that mitigate these risks, demonstrating a thoughtful approach to ethical considerations in data science. If students are struggling to think of additional concerns, here are some example responses you could use with students to help them get started:\n* In today's lesson, when we created histograms, I realized how choosing different bin sizes could change how the data looked. This made me think about accuracy and how important it is to represent data truthfully without manipulating the viewer’s perception.\n* You mentioned privacy concerns with mapping data. In our exercise, we didn't use personal data, but it made me think about how companies might use similar techniques with personal data. We should always ensure data anonymization before creating such visualizations to protect individual identities.\n* You mentioned misuse of data. When we use powerful tools like Google Sheets to analyze data, it's crucial to think about the consequences of our analysis. For instance, if we're identifying trends that might influence decision-making in businesses or government, we need to be extra cautious about confirming our findings."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1a18a662-dbd4-4c9e-a101-83487f9b8377",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b533a95b-12cb-4b80-b189-f864db677aa9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "18e0257c-4942-408e-9f7b-fabf744732a6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Review the lesson objectives.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to their Unit Guides to answer the Question of the Day and give students 30 seconds to write a response. Have them share with a partner or read a few aloud.\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "This way of working with the Question of the Day works well as an exit ticket or a quick way to gauge comprehension during a lesson."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "18e0257c-4942-408e-9f7b-fabf744732a6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "57dda77f-538d-4cf7-9c06-5ca2614aa115"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "553c5e26-641a-4efd-912b-6b20acd4bba0",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *How do the types of parties change as kids age?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should identify how party preferences shift from simpler themes to more adventurous and sophisticated activities as kids grow older.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Warm Up",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to think about why these trends occur and what factors influence these changes. Help students see the relevance of analyzing data to uncover trends and patterns, setting the stage for their own data investigations."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "553c5e26-641a-4efd-912b-6b20acd4bba0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "33c6ed89-260b-4179-b438-c2e7f7c09c2b",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "33c6ed89-260b-4179-b438-c2e7f7c09c2b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "192991fa-e16d-413a-a230-f1beb05a849d",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In your upcoming project, you'll get to explore your own data questions and uncover interesting trends just like this. Let's dive into the project guide to see what you'll be working on!",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "192991fa-e16d-413a-a230-f1beb05a849d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0f5d302b-eaec-46b7-a5b3-91eb3b423efc",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-file-text-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Distribute:** Give each student a copy of the Crafting Stories with Data Project Planning Guide. This will guide them through all four days of the project.",
        "duration": "35",
        "name": "Activity"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0f5d302b-eaec-46b7-a5b3-91eb3b423efc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "749cdd68-835d-42ca-85a5-dfd4dde63801",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "For the next four days, we will be making our own data stories and answering data questions about data sets that we will be choosing today. As a class, let’s go over the project guide to make sure we understand what we will be doing for the next several days.",
        "remarks": true,
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "This project will be completed on individual computers by individual students. However, it may be helpful to assign \"thought partners\" so that students have a peer to discuss and share their ideas with."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "749cdd68-835d-42ca-85a5-dfd4dde63801",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ee10dd82-c99a-41c5-87f1-6822feaf0d10",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to explain the project requirements.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Discussing the Project Requirements is part of the **Understand** step of the UMPIRE strategy. It helps students ensure they have a strong foundation from which to make their plan.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ee10dd82-c99a-41c5-87f1-6822feaf0d10",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "77cbe19c-c1a7-4992-9492-881a4cbb3e8b",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to read the project rubric and hold on to any questions they may have. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What do you notice about the project rubric?*\n* *What does success look like for this project?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students share what they notice about the project requirements and rubric and identify the tasks they will need to complete for this project.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *What barriers do you anticipate to achieving success on this project?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students identify barriers they anticipate and share any questions they have about the project.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the steps students will take on Day 1.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Encourage students to refer back to UMPIRE as they work through the project. Remind students that the AI chatbot can be used to help them **Make a plan** (brainstorming, exploring their dataset, creating visualizations, etc) as well as the **Inspect** step to get feedback and the **Refine** step to iterate and improve their visualizations or data story.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "77cbe19c-c1a7-4992-9492-881a4cbb3e8b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b1bdc470-0f2f-42f9-a3a6-97aa0bbdcb7d",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the steps students will take on Days 2 and 3.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Point out to students that they will be spending two days on these steps which means the data question they land on should not be an extremely simple one. Challenge students to investigate a data question that might require deep analysis or several visualizations to help them answer it."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b1bdc470-0f2f-42f9-a3a6-97aa0bbdcb7d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "54a06cde-80dd-42e2-bb54-d144ecddbf26",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "54a06cde-80dd-42e2-bb54-d144ecddbf26",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "28b71b16-b67a-4d72-adaf-edc70baacccb",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to introduce the steps students will take on Day 4.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If you have time, you might decide to extend this project to five days in order to allow students to share their projects with one another."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "28b71b16-b67a-4d72-adaf-edc70baacccb",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "811bd9ab-d923-407e-a9cd-3bf79f2ddab4",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "811bd9ab-d923-407e-a9cd-3bf79f2ddab4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e3f997c6-860b-49ce-8367-d1a7f7f65ab7",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Group students into pairs. Each student will complete the project and all of its levels individually, but they should work with a thought partner to help them talk about the data. Make sure students are clear that while their partner should act as a thought partner, they should complete the project individually.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "You may wish to allow students to choose data sets before they get into partners, and partner students who are interested in similar data sets. This ensures students are matched by interest and aren’t limited by what both of them are interested in, but it also means that some students may pick data sets nobody else does and thus wind up without a thought partner or having to change the data set they’re using."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e3f997c6-860b-49ce-8367-d1a7f7f65ab7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "aa6e56f8-9b2f-47d4-9e0c-bed1fa7618a7",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "aa6e56f8-9b2f-47d4-9e0c-bed1fa7618a7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "97f37a43-96ce-4177-bae1-ea954188a1b5",
      "position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 1 to choose a data set. Instruct them to do a Three Reads on their chosen data set in their project planning guide.",
        "progression_name": "Data Set Choices",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "By this point, students should be familiar enough with Three Reads to not require regrouping with the entire class after each read. They will probably find data sets at different rates and should not necessarily all be on the same read at the same time. That said, you should still use the next few slides to help encourage students to keep a pace that will allow them to complete their three reads on time. Additionally, these slides serve as useful prompts, reminding students of the specific questions they should consider about the data during each reading."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "97f37a43-96ce-4177-bae1-ea954188a1b5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b61833eb-bc79-4883-a30c-ee2d745b21e8",
      "position": 15,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b61833eb-bc79-4883-a30c-ee2d745b21e8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0ffec2d5-cec2-4a7f-88bc-252bc8eb5c20",
      "position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Facilitate a Three Reads about the students’ chosen data sets. Unlike previous three reads, there does not need to be a share out. Students will go through their three reads at different rates, but these slides still exist to encourage students to not spend too much time picking a data set or on any particular read.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Help students who are having trouble picking a dataset make a decision.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Facilitate Read 2 for data set. It is ok if not all students have reached Read 2 yet – students may take differing amounts of time choosing a data set in the first place – but you should remind students to keep moving forward.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Help students who have not yet reached Read 2 answer the questions from Read 1.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Facilitate Read 3 for students’ data set. Remind students to consider the RSAIR criteria when forming data questions about their data set. Unlike previous Three Reads, students will not do an informal sharing of their ideas with a partner. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If you have time and feel your students would benefit, consider conducting a peer review of the data question students are considering for their project. Use the (Optional) Data Question Peer Review activity guide."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0ffec2d5-cec2-4a7f-88bc-252bc8eb5c20",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fef743e7-13ef-4f63-aede-5d7d60fa961c",
      "position": 17,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fef743e7-13ef-4f63-aede-5d7d60fa961c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4c0763d7-da0b-450c-a8c0-052e112c14c1",
      "position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Let’s see how AI can help you sharpen your question and push it further using the RSAIR criteria.Think of AI as your revision partner. Ask it for feedback, take what’s useful, and use it to make your question stronger.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4c0763d7-da0b-450c-a8c0-052e112c14c1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "19fc4a05-696d-4229-afdd-fc99ff3cd119",
      "position": 19,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to move on to Level 5 and open AI Chat to begin evaluating their question.",
        "progression_name": "AI Data Coach",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Throughout the project, remind students that AI Chat can act as a “data coach.” Encourage them to use it anytime they need help refining their data question, interpreting a graph, or improving their final story. A great check-in prompt is: “What helpful suggestion did AI give you?” This keeps AI use purposeful and student-driven."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "19fc4a05-696d-4229-afdd-fc99ff3cd119",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "64e01b88-ac16-4704-b243-049d4b11cdf9",
      "position": 20,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to complete the Day 1 Reflection questions in their project planning guide. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are discussing these reflection questions with their thought partner and going through the RSAIR criteria for the data question they are thinking about investigating. This is an opportunity for students to refine their data questions if needed based on their discussions.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Wrap Up",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If there is time, you may wish to have students share out their answers to these questions. This will give you an idea of the questions they are investigating as well as give other students an idea of what questions others are going to investigate."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "These reflection questions can be used as a formative assessment of students ability to select a data set and form RSAIR data questions."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "64e01b88-ac16-4704-b243-049d4b11cdf9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "28e8ee8d-d3d8-4ce1-a0a9-2b467e02071d"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e9a49c38-e6c0-4f7b-934f-d0c35a428dcd",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What data question are you going to investigate?*\n* *How does your question meet the RSAIR criteria?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to share the data questions they will investigate and how they meets the RSAIR criteria. This is an opportunity for students to once again, refine their data question if needed. ",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Warm Up",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Remind students that are about to spend the next two days investigating their data question and gaining insights via visualizations, so the data question they land on should not be an extremely simple one. Challenge students to investigate a data question that might require deep analysis or several visualizations to help them answer it."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e9a49c38-e6c0-4f7b-934f-d0c35a428dcd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68630a55-dc3e-40de-859f-e48698369f58"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7a4d42f4-6084-4456-8cb8-0ce38593f2c6",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Today, we’ll start analyzing our data, seeing what insights we can gain. But first, you may need to make some decisions with your data. ",
        "duration": "30",
        "name": "Activity",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7a4d42f4-6084-4456-8cb8-0ce38593f2c6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68630a55-dc3e-40de-859f-e48698369f58"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a445886c-bdf0-43ff-bb23-3005ee18192f",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Click through the animated slide to show examples of the decisions they may need to make with their dataset."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a445886c-bdf0-43ff-bb23-3005ee18192f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68630a55-dc3e-40de-859f-e48698369f58"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "288292d9-c3d7-469e-a14d-d37836d7f820",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "For example, do you need to clean it? Do you need to sort or filter your data? Do you need to use the SUM(), COUNTIF(), or AVERAGE() functions we learned about? You may not even realize you need to do some of that until you get in and start making visualizations to try to answer your data question.\n",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "288292d9-c3d7-469e-a14d-d37836d7f820",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68630a55-dc3e-40de-859f-e48698369f58"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a9b8523b-61fc-40de-a4f1-a741cf50d2ec",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Something else you might notice as that as you create your visualizations, you spark new questions – that’s fine! Ask those questions and make more visualizations; your data stories should be made up of more than one visualization. If your data question ends up changing, that is also fine. Use the visualizations to help you form questions. This is an iterative process!",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a9b8523b-61fc-40de-a4f1-a741cf50d2ec",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68630a55-dc3e-40de-859f-e48698369f58"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3948267e-c1ac-49dd-9379-d71ff8ab1e61",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 2 to work with their data and create visualizations.",
        "progression_name": "Data Decisions and Visualizations",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Creating visualizations is reflective of the **Produce** step of the UMPIRE strategy."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3948267e-c1ac-49dd-9379-d71ff8ab1e61",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68630a55-dc3e-40de-859f-e48698369f58"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a1c1c499-9209-4109-ba67-d65506fdf26f",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are on task. Encourage students to share and discuss their visualizations and potential insights they provide with a thought partner while working. As you move around the room, engage students with questions about their data decisions and their visualizations. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a1c1c499-9209-4109-ba67-d65506fdf26f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68630a55-dc3e-40de-859f-e48698369f58"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "db831bb8-13ed-46f5-a3ef-eb9ace29e919",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "db831bb8-13ed-46f5-a3ef-eb9ace29e919",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68630a55-dc3e-40de-859f-e48698369f58"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2a743e82-3b5f-4cb6-a000-d3d78216609a",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Now that you've created your graph, let’s use AI Chat as a data coach. It can help you figure out what story your graph is telling or help you sharpen your question before you move on.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2a743e82-3b5f-4cb6-a000-d3d78216609a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68630a55-dc3e-40de-859f-e48698369f58"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2bec6326-be5d-4fb6-9771-54ca34065f50",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to move on to Level 5 to use AI Chat to interpret their graph or make their data question more specific."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2bec6326-be5d-4fb6-9771-54ca34065f50",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68630a55-dc3e-40de-859f-e48698369f58"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b03824d2-b45a-4f4e-9dfd-89e2ad862edc",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What did you accomplish today?*\n* *What do you need to do next?*\n* *What obstacles are in your way?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to discuss the decisions they made with their data and the visualizations they created today. They should discuss either needing to create more or different visualizations next class or looking at their visualizations to really start analyzing them. Students should share any obstacles they may have and discuss possible solutions. ",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Wrap Up",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "These reflection questions can be used as a formative assessment of students ability to create visualizations that will help them answer their data questions. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b03824d2-b45a-4f4e-9dfd-89e2ad862edc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "68630a55-dc3e-40de-859f-e48698369f58"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ce56df17-bfd4-4700-80fb-f9c2caf70505",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** Click through the animated slide to display the prompts.\n* *What type of graphs did you create last class?*\n* *Have you identified any patterns, trends, or outliers so far?*\n* *How did they help you analyze and gain insights into your data and data question?*\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should be able to identify the types of graphs and charts they created as well as share any insights they gained from them. ",
        "duration": "10",
        "name": "Warm Up"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ce56df17-bfd4-4700-80fb-f9c2caf70505",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9dc8cc9e-95a7-46c6-a7d9-223793f2ee2c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "277c995a-6f16-432b-a341-63320a81926b",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Today is your last day to create any visualizations that could help you answer your data question and tell your data story. It is also the last day for you to sit down with those visualizations and really analyze what they are telling you about your data and your data question. So, even if you think you have created the visualizations you need, it will be wise to ensure you have looked at your question from all angles and have really thought about the insights your data is giving you and found all potential evidence to support your answer to your data question. ",
        "duration": "30",
        "name": "Activity",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "277c995a-6f16-432b-a341-63320a81926b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9dc8cc9e-95a7-46c6-a7d9-223793f2ee2c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "898cecca-222d-4d14-933c-2d56d8bb237d",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 2 to work with their data and create visualizations."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "898cecca-222d-4d14-933c-2d56d8bb237d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9dc8cc9e-95a7-46c6-a7d9-223793f2ee2c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0b1083dc-09f9-4c4c-995e-290bae8a217c",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are on task. Encourage students to sharing and discuss their visualizations and potential insights and evidence they provide with a thought partner while working. As you move around the room, engage students with questions about their data decisions and their visualizations. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0b1083dc-09f9-4c4c-995e-290bae8a217c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9dc8cc9e-95a7-46c6-a7d9-223793f2ee2c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ca804888-6bb7-4234-a914-ca6dfee13387",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to move on to Level 5 to use AI Chat to interpret their graph or make their data question more specific."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ca804888-6bb7-4234-a914-ca6dfee13387",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9dc8cc9e-95a7-46c6-a7d9-223793f2ee2c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4f94b56e-ebde-4f74-a5fd-1d2eb1569230",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to complete the Day 2-3 Reflection questions in their project planning guide.",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Wrap Up",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If there is time, you may wish to allow students to share some of their answers to these questions. This will give you an idea of where they are as well as give other students an idea of what is working for their peers and what they are struggling with."
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "These reflection questions can be used as a formative assessment of students ability to create visualizations and use them to gain insights into their data question. "
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4f94b56e-ebde-4f74-a5fd-1d2eb1569230",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9dc8cc9e-95a7-46c6-a7d9-223793f2ee2c"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "965d1be4-7ddf-46f0-a5f8-9d3062c2df6a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Instruct students to have their project guide out and take a moment to \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Which sentence starters from the table on Day 4 might work best for your data story?*\n\n* Conduct a Think/Pair/Share protocol in order to give students a moment to look at the context, shape of distribution, measures of center, etc that they will be writing about today and identify which sentence starters they might use before they share with a partner and then the whole class. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** The goal is to give students an opportunity to start thinking and discussing with a partner about which sentence starters might work best for them. ",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Warm Up"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "965d1be4-7ddf-46f0-a5f8-9d3062c2df6a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c47c73da-bf54-4c55-8fc4-ebbc73b83e26"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "953c9b4a-b1bd-443f-9065-8a493d891c28",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to begin writing their data stories in their activity guide. Remind them to use the language in the sentence starter table in their project guide. Encourage them to use bullet points for each aspect of their response (context, shape of distribution, measures of center, etc) for this first draft.",
        "duration": "35",
        "name": "Activity",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Give students about five minutes for this first, quick, rough draft. It is not necessary for students to have completely finished their response during this time as they will have an opportunity to share, discuss, and iterate before their final response."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "953c9b4a-b1bd-443f-9065-8a493d891c28",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c47c73da-bf54-4c55-8fc4-ebbc73b83e26"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "842736f4-68cd-4d76-a76c-039e3b5d90ed",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "842736f4-68cd-4d76-a76c-039e3b5d90ed",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c47c73da-bf54-4c55-8fc4-ebbc73b83e26"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6b083c27-e8a9-4741-98e1-1327be6e9e0f",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are working and that all the students have written this first draft using bullet points in order to gather their thoughts. Ease any concerns for students that are worried they won’t finish this first, quick rough draft and let them know this is just to help them get started and they will have time to update and add on to what they’ve started. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Have students find a partner then take turns answering their data question out loud. Encourage them to try to do so without reading what they wrote in the project guide. Students should record ideas from their discussions that they want to use in their final responses. ",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If you have time, you can conduct a second round of peer discussions to allow students to talk about their data question and response with another peer."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6b083c27-e8a9-4741-98e1-1327be6e9e0f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c47c73da-bf54-4c55-8fc4-ebbc73b83e26"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b0ab0d7c-51a9-4be5-b67f-563a9641b66c",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b0ab0d7c-51a9-4be5-b67f-563a9641b66c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c47c73da-bf54-4c55-8fc4-ebbc73b83e26"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6ad9c55d-9d04-4e25-a53e-65420a421cad",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-desktop\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Transition:** Direct students to Level 3 to record their final response and upload their visualization(s). Remind students to describe their data using the sentence starters, answer their data question, and add evidence.",
        "progression_name": "Your Data Story",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Creating a data story is reflective of the **Produce** step of the UMPIRE strategy.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6ad9c55d-9d04-4e25-a53e-65420a421cad",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c47c73da-bf54-4c55-8fc4-ebbc73b83e26"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6ce37adb-b2e8-49d4-9286-b9ec31e4b1f7",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are on task and are using data science terms from the sentence starters to answer their data question and tell their data story.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Student’s final responses can be used as an assessment of their knowledge and skills for this chapter. You can use the provided rubric to guide your assessment."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6ce37adb-b2e8-49d4-9286-b9ec31e4b1f7",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c47c73da-bf54-4c55-8fc4-ebbc73b83e26"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "aa75ca90-2162-4251-bd8a-4be2d501448c",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "aa75ca90-2162-4251-bd8a-4be2d501448c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c47c73da-bf54-4c55-8fc4-ebbc73b83e26"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "11e65721-500a-4c14-a31a-b0bb821885a8",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Do This:** Direct students to Level 4 to describe their process through the data cycle and any ethical considerations they took into account throughout the project, such as privacy, bias, or misuse.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Circulate:** Ensure students are on task. Provide any support needed to students as they describe each step of the process through the data cycle. As they are writing about the ethical considerations, which could include privacy, bias or misrepresentation of the data, remind them to think about all aspects of the process, including any ethical concerns they considered when selecting their data set, making decisions with their dataset, creating visualizations, and answering their data questions. ",
        "progression_name": "The Data Cycle",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Student’s final responses can be used as an assessment of their knowledge and skills for this chapter. You can use the provided rubric to guide your assessment. Student’s project guides can also be collected and used as part of the assessment. There may be some reflection questions that could be taken into account when assessing their project according to the rubric.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "11e65721-500a-4c14-a31a-b0bb821885a8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c47c73da-bf54-4c55-8fc4-ebbc73b83e26"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a48bc662-16c6-4de1-9ad3-22e84447f2ee",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discuss:** *Click through the animated slide to display the discussion prompts:*\n* _What are two things about your project that you are proud of?_\n* _If you had to tell a different data story with your same dataset, what might it be?_\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Discussion Goal:** Students should reflect on their work throughout this unit and what they were able to accomplish in their final project. They should also be able to articulate that a single dataset can lead to different data stories and interpretations. ",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Wrap Up",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Consider having students present their work to each other. You might want to group students by dataset so they can see the different data questions and data stories their classmates came up with for the same data.\n"
          },
          {
            "type": "assessmentOpportunity",
            "markdown": "Once students have completed this last reflection, their project guide can be collected and used as part of the assessment. There may be some reflection questions that could be taken into account when assessing their project according to the rubric."
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a48bc662-16c6-4de1-9ad3-22e84447f2ee",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c47c73da-bf54-4c55-8fc4-ebbc73b83e26"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cf123407-01ce-4c68-9a57-969b58fe352b",
